// FinLearnX – Premium Course Pages (25 pages each, unique content per course)
export const COURSE_PAGES = {};

// ─── Helper ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
function p(ch, pg, title, sub, body, points, hl, ex) {
  return { ch, pg, title, sub, body, points, highlight: hl, example: ex };
}

// ─── VALUE INVESTING (25 pages) ──────────────────────────────────────────────
COURSE_PAGES['value-investing'] = [
  p(1,1,'What is Value Investing?','The Philosophy That Created the World\'s Greatest Investors',`Value investing is the practice of buying securities priced below their intrinsic value. Pioneered by Benjamin Graham and perfected by Warren Buffett, it is the most proven wealth-building strategy in history.\n\nThe core idea: the stock market is a voting machine short-term but a weighing machine long-term. Prices are driven by emotion short-term; they converge to true value long-term.\n\nValue investors exploit the gap between price and value — buying when the market is pessimistic and prices are below intrinsic value, then waiting patiently for the market to recognize true worth.`,['Price is what you pay; Value is what you get — Buffett','Market is irrational short-term, rational long-term','Requires patience, discipline, independent thinking','Graham\'s Security Analysis (1934) is the bible of value investing','Buffett turned $100 into $100B+ using these principles'],'💡 "In the short run, the market is a voting machine. In the long run, it is a weighing machine." — Benjamin Graham','In 2008, Buffett bought Goldman Sachs preferred shares at $5B during panic. By 2013, this returned $3.7B profit — a 74% gain in 5 years.'),
  p(1,2,'History of Value Investing','From Graham to Buffett to Modern Masters',`Value investing has a 90-year history of outperforming the market. Benjamin Graham (1894–1976) developed the intellectual framework at Columbia Business School. His books Security Analysis (1934) and The Intelligent Investor (1949) remain definitive texts.\n\nWarren Buffett studied under Graham at Columbia, then evolved the purely quantitative approach by incorporating qualitative factors — brand strength, management quality, competitive moats — concepts from Charlie Munger and Philip Fisher.\n\nToday, value investing is practiced by the world's most successful investors including Seth Klarman, Howard Marks, and Joel Greenblatt.`,['1934: Graham publishes Security Analysis','1949: The Intelligent Investor — "best book on investing ever written" (Buffett)','1956: Buffett starts partnership with $105,000','1965: Buffett takes control of Berkshire Hathaway','2024: Berkshire worth over $900 billion'],'💡 Buffett\'s net worth grew from $1M at age 30 to $100B+ at age 90 — entirely through value investing.','Berkshire compounded at ~20% annually for 58 years vs S&P 500\'s ~10%. $1,000 in 1965: Berkshire = $36M vs S&P 500 = $235,000.'),
  p(1,3,'The 5 Core Principles','Pillars Every Value Investor Must Master',`Value investing rests on five foundational principles. Master these and you will have a significant edge over 95% of market participants.\n\nPrinciple 1 — Intrinsic Value: Every business has an intrinsic value based on future cash flows, estimable through careful analysis.\n\nPrinciple 2 — Margin of Safety: Always buy at significant discount to intrinsic value. Graham recommended buying at 2/3 of intrinsic value or less.\n\nPrinciple 3 — Mr. Market: Treat the market as a manic-depressive partner offering wildly varying prices. Use his irrationality to your advantage.\n\nPrinciple 4 — Circle of Competence: Only invest in businesses you understand deeply.\n\nPrinciple 5 — Long-Term Orientation: Value investing requires patience. Buffett\'s average holding period is 20+ years.`,['Intrinsic Value = Present value of all future cash flows','Margin of Safety = Buy 30–50% below intrinsic value','Mr. Market = Your servant, not your master','Circle of Competence = Only invest in what you understand','Long-term = Think in decades, not quarters'],'💡 "The stock market is designed to transfer money from the Active to the Patient." — Warren Buffett','Buffett bought Coca-Cola in 1988 at $1.3B. Today that stake is worth $25B+. He has never sold a single share in 36 years.'),
  p(2,1,'Mr. Market — Your Greatest Ally','Benjamin Graham\'s Most Powerful Mental Model',`Imagine you own a small business with a partner named Mr. Market. Every day, Mr. Market offers to buy your share or sell you his share at a specific price.\n\nThe key insight: Mr. Market is emotionally unstable. Some days he is euphoric and offers absurdly high prices. Other days he is depressed and offers ridiculously low prices. You are never obligated to trade with him.\n\nThe intelligent investor uses Mr. Market\'s emotional swings to their advantage. When Mr. Market is depressed and offers low prices, you buy. When he is euphoric and offers high prices, you sell. The rest of the time, you ignore him completely.`,['Mr. Market is your servant, not your guide','Market prices are offers, not verdicts on value','Volatility is opportunity, not risk for value investors','The market is most dangerous when it feels safest','The market is most attractive when it feels most dangerous'],'💡 "Be fearful when others are greedy, and greedy when others are fearful." — Warren Buffett','March 2020 COVID crash: Nifty fell 38% in 6 weeks. Mr. Market was in extreme panic. Investors who bought during this period earned 100%+ returns within 18 months.'),
  p(2,2,'Margin of Safety','The Three Most Important Words in Investing',`"Margin of Safety" is the central concept of value investing. It means buying a security at a price significantly below its estimated intrinsic value, providing a cushion against errors in analysis or unexpected negative events.\n\nGraham recommended buying stocks at no more than 2/3 of their net asset value for deep value stocks, or at a significant discount to their earnings power value.\n\nThe margin of safety serves three purposes:\n1. Protection against analytical errors — your intrinsic value estimate may be wrong\n2. Protection against business deterioration — the business may perform worse than expected\n3. Enhanced returns — buying cheap means more upside when price converges to value`,['Buy at 30–50% below intrinsic value for adequate margin of safety','Larger margin of safety = Lower risk + Higher potential return','Protects against errors in analysis and business deterioration','Graham: "Margin of safety is the secret of sound investment"','Buffett: "Rule 1 — Never lose money. Rule 2 — Never forget Rule 1"'],'💡 Margin of Safety is like buying a ₹100 note for ₹60. Even if you are wrong about the value, you have significant protection.','If intrinsic value = ₹1,000/share and you buy at ₹600 (40% margin of safety): Even if you overestimated value by 20% (true value = ₹800), you still make 33% profit.'),
  p(2,3,'Understanding Market Cycles','How to Profit from Market Irrationality',`Markets move in cycles driven by human psychology. Understanding these cycles allows value investors to systematically buy low and sell high — not through market timing, but through valuation discipline.\n\nPhase 1 — Accumulation: Smart money buys after a crash. Sentiment is negative, prices are low, valuations are attractive.\nPhase 2 — Markup: Prices rise as fundamentals improve. Institutional investors buy. Sentiment turns positive.\nPhase 3 — Distribution: Smart money sells to retail investors at high prices. Sentiment is euphoric. Valuations are stretched.\nPhase 4 — Markdown: Prices fall as reality sets in. Retail investors panic and sell. Cycle repeats.`,['Market cycles are driven by fear and greed, not fundamentals','Nifty P/E below 15 = Attractive buying zone historically','Nifty P/E above 25 = Caution zone, reduce equity allocation','Market cap to GDP below 75% = Undervalued market (India)','Buffett Indicator: Market Cap/GDP above 100% = Overvalued'],'💡 "The four most dangerous words in investing: This time is different." — Sir John Templeton','India Nifty P/E in March 2020: 17x (attractive). By October 2021: 28x (expensive). Investors who bought in March 2020 and sold in late 2021 made 100%+ returns.'),
  p(3,1,'Intrinsic Value Calculation','The Art and Science of Business Valuation',`Intrinsic value is the present value of all future cash flows a business will generate. Calculating it requires estimating future earnings, growth rates, and an appropriate discount rate.\n\nThe Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) method is the most rigorous approach:\n1. Estimate free cash flows for the next 5–10 years\n2. Estimate a terminal value beyond the forecast period\n3. Discount all cash flows back to present value using WACC\n4. Sum all discounted cash flows = Intrinsic Value\n\nGraham\'s simpler approach: Intrinsic Value = EPS × (8.5 + 2g) × 4.4/Y\nWhere g = expected growth rate, Y = current AAA bond yield`,['DCF = Most rigorous valuation method','Graham Formula: IV = EPS × (8.5 + 2g) × 4.4/Y','Always use conservative growth rate estimates','Intrinsic value is a range, not a precise number','Margin of safety compensates for estimation errors'],'💡 "It is better to be approximately right than precisely wrong." — Warren Buffett','Infosys FY2024: EPS = ₹65, Growth = 12%, Bond yield = 7.5%. Graham IV = 65 × (8.5 + 24) × 4.4/7.5 = ₹1,241. If trading at ₹800, margin of safety = 35%.'),
  p(3,2,'Financial Statement Analysis','Reading the Language of Business',`Value investors must be fluent in financial statements. The three key statements are the Income Statement, Balance Sheet, and Cash Flow Statement.\n\nIncome Statement: Shows revenue, expenses, and profit over a period. Key metrics: Revenue growth, Gross margin, Operating margin, Net profit margin, EPS.\n\nBalance Sheet: Shows assets, liabilities, and equity at a point in time. Key metrics: Debt-to-equity ratio, Current ratio, Book value per share, Return on equity.\n\nCash Flow Statement: Shows actual cash generated and used. Key metrics: Operating cash flow, Free cash flow, Capital expenditure, Cash conversion cycle.`,['Revenue growth shows business momentum','Gross margin reveals pricing power and competitive advantage','Free Cash Flow is more important than reported earnings','Debt-to-equity below 1 is generally safe for most businesses','ROE above 15% consistently indicates a quality business'],'💡 "Accounting is the language of business. You have to be as comfortable with it as you are with your own language." — Warren Buffett','Reliance Industries FY2024: Revenue ₹9.7L Cr, Net Profit ₹79,020 Cr, Free Cash Flow ₹45,000 Cr, ROE 9.8%, Debt/Equity 0.4 — financially strong business.'),
  p(3,3,'Identifying Economic Moats','The Secret to Long-Term Wealth Creation',`An economic moat is a sustainable competitive advantage that protects a company from competition. Companies with wide moats can maintain high returns on capital for decades.\n\nTypes of Economic Moats:\n1. Network Effects: Value increases as more users join (Visa, NSE)\n2. Cost Advantages: Produce at lower cost than competitors (Asian Paints)\n3. Switching Costs: Expensive or difficult for customers to switch (Tally, SAP)\n4. Intangible Assets: Brands, patents, licenses (Nestle, Pidilite, Colgate)\n5. Efficient Scale: Natural monopoly in limited market (airport operators, utilities)`,['Wide moat companies can sustain high ROE for 10+ years','Network effects are the most powerful moat type','Brand moats are visible in pricing power and customer loyalty','Switching cost moats create recurring revenue streams','Always ask: What prevents competitors from taking market share?'],'💡 "The key to investing is not assessing how much an industry is going to affect society, but rather determining the competitive advantage of any given company." — Warren Buffett','Asian Paints has maintained 20%+ ROE for 20+ consecutive years due to its distribution network moat — 70,000+ dealer network that competitors cannot replicate.'),
  p(4,1,'Warren Buffett\'s Investment Framework','The Complete Checklist of the World\'s Greatest Investor',`Warren Buffett evaluates investments using a comprehensive framework that combines Graham\'s quantitative discipline with Fisher\'s qualitative analysis.\n\nBuffett\'s 4 Key Questions:\n1. Is the business understandable? (Circle of Competence)\n2. Does the business have a durable competitive advantage? (Moat)\n3. Is management honest and competent? (Management Quality)\n4. Is the price attractive? (Valuation)\n\nBuffett\'s Ideal Business Characteristics:\n- High and consistent return on equity (15%+ for 10+ years)\n- Low capital requirements (asset-light business model)\n- Strong free cash flow generation\n- Pricing power (ability to raise prices without losing customers)`,['Only invest in businesses you can understand in 5 minutes','Management integrity is non-negotiable — avoid dishonest managers','Pricing power is the single most important business characteristic','Asset-light businesses compound capital more efficiently','"It\'s far better to buy a wonderful company at a fair price than a fair company at a wonderful price"'],'💡 "I look for businesses in which I think I can predict what they will look like in ten to fifteen years time." — Warren Buffett','Buffett\'s investment in See\'s Candies (1972): Paid $25M. Has generated $2B+ in cumulative pre-tax earnings. The ultimate example of a wide-moat, asset-light business.'),
  p(4,2,'Qualitative Analysis','Beyond the Numbers — Understanding Business Quality',`Numbers tell you what happened; qualitative analysis tells you why and whether it will continue. The best value investors combine rigorous quantitative analysis with deep qualitative understanding.\n\nKey Qualitative Factors:\n\nManagement Quality: Study the CEO\'s track record, capital allocation decisions, shareholder letters, and compensation structure. Great managers are honest, competent, and shareholder-oriented.\n\nIndustry Dynamics: Understand the competitive landscape, industry growth rate, regulatory environment, and technological disruption risks.\n\nPhilip Fisher\'s Scuttlebutt Method: Talk to customers, suppliers, competitors, and former employees to get a complete picture of the business.`,['Management quality determines long-term business outcomes','Study annual reports and shareholder letters for 5+ years','Great capital allocators create disproportionate shareholder value','Industry tailwinds make investing easier; headwinds make it harder','Scuttlebutt: Talk to people who know the business intimately'],'💡 "I\'d rather have a first-class management team running a second-class business than a second-class team running a first-class business." — Warren Buffett','Infosys under Narayana Murthy: Built a $100B company from scratch through exceptional management quality, ethical governance, and consistent capital allocation.'),
  p(4,3,'Building a Value Portfolio','Constructing a Concentrated, High-Conviction Portfolio',`Value investors typically hold concentrated portfolios of 10–20 high-conviction positions rather than diversifying across hundreds of stocks. This concentration allows for deep research and higher returns.\n\nPortfolio Construction Principles:\n1. Position Sizing: Allocate more to highest-conviction ideas (10–20% per position)\n2. Diversification: Spread across sectors and business types\n3. Patience: Hold positions for years, not months\n4. Rebalancing: Add to positions when they become cheaper; trim when they become expensive\n5. Cash Management: Hold cash when no attractive opportunities exist`,['10–20 positions is optimal for a value portfolio','Highest conviction ideas deserve largest allocations','Hold cash when no attractive opportunities exist','Never sell a great business just because it has risen','Add to positions during market corrections'],'💡 "Wide diversification is only required when investors do not understand what they are doing." — Warren Buffett','Buffett\'s top 5 holdings (Apple, Bank of America, Chevron, Coca-Cola, American Express) represent 75%+ of Berkshire\'s equity portfolio — extreme concentration.'),
  p(5,1,'Value Investing in Indian Markets','Applying Graham-Buffett Framework to NSE/BSE',`Indian markets offer exceptional opportunities for value investors due to information asymmetry, retail investor dominance, and the presence of many high-quality businesses at reasonable valuations.\n\nUnique Characteristics of Indian Markets:\n- Dominated by retail investors (70%+ of trading volume) who are often emotional\n- Many family-owned businesses with strong promoter alignment\n- High economic growth rate (6–8% GDP) provides tailwind for businesses\n- Regulatory improvements (SEBI) have improved corporate governance\n- Emerging middle class driving consumption growth for decades`,['Indian markets are less efficient than US markets — more opportunities','Focus on businesses serving India\'s growing middle class','Promoter-owned businesses often have better long-term alignment','Avoid companies with frequent equity dilution or related-party transactions','SEBI regulations have significantly improved corporate governance'],'💡 India\'s GDP is expected to reach $10 trillion by 2035 — the biggest wealth creation opportunity of our generation.','Titan Company: Bought at ₹100 in 2010, now ₹3,500+ in 2024 — a 35x return in 14 years. Classic example of a wide-moat Indian consumer brand.'),
  p(5,2,'Common Value Traps','Stocks That Look Cheap But Are Not',`A value trap is a stock that appears cheap based on traditional metrics but continues to decline because the underlying business is deteriorating. Avoiding value traps is as important as finding genuine value.\n\nCommon Value Trap Characteristics:\n1. Declining Industry: Cheap for a reason — the industry is structurally declining\n2. Accounting Issues: Low P/E due to inflated earnings that will not be sustained\n3. Debt Trap: Low P/B but high debt that will destroy equity value\n4. Management Problems: Cheap stock with dishonest or incompetent management\n5. Commodity Business: Low margins, no pricing power, cyclical earnings`,['Always ask: Why is this stock cheap?','Declining industries rarely recover — avoid structural decline','High debt amplifies both gains and losses','Management integrity issues are almost never resolved','Commodity businesses rarely create long-term shareholder value'],'💡 "It\'s much better to buy a wonderful company at a fair price than a fair company at a wonderful price." — Warren Buffett','Jet Airways: Looked cheap at ₹200 in 2018 (down from ₹800). Was a classic value trap — high debt, poor management, structural industry problems. Went bankrupt in 2019.'),
  p(5,3,'When to Sell','The Most Difficult Decision in Value Investing',`Knowing when to sell is as important as knowing when to buy. Value investors sell for three main reasons:\n\n1. Valuation: The stock has reached or exceeded intrinsic value. The margin of safety has disappeared.\n\n2. Fundamental Deterioration: The business has changed for the worse. The moat has been eroded. Management has made poor decisions.\n\n3. Better Opportunity: A significantly better investment opportunity has been identified and capital needs to be redeployed.\n\nWhat NOT to do:\n- Do not sell just because the stock has risen significantly\n- Do not sell because of short-term market volatility`,['Sell when price significantly exceeds intrinsic value','Sell when the investment thesis has been broken','Sell when a significantly better opportunity exists','Never sell a great business just because it has risen','Tax implications should be considered but not drive sell decisions'],'💡 "Our favorite holding period is forever." — Warren Buffett (for truly exceptional businesses)','Buffett has held Coca-Cola since 1988 (36 years) and American Express since 1964 (60 years). He has never sold despite both stocks rising 50–100x.'),
  p(6,1,'Advanced Valuation Methods','DCF, Relative Valuation, and Sum-of-Parts',`Professional value investors use multiple valuation methods and triangulate to arrive at a range of intrinsic value estimates.\n\nMethod 1 — Discounted Cash Flow (DCF): Most rigorous but most sensitive to assumptions. Best for stable, predictable businesses.\n\nMethod 2 — Relative Valuation: Compare P/E, P/B, EV/EBITDA to industry peers and historical averages. Best for cyclical businesses and quick screening.\n\nMethod 3 — Sum-of-Parts (SOTP): Value each business segment separately and add them up. Best for conglomerates like Reliance, Tata Group companies.\n\nMethod 4 — Asset-Based Valuation: Value the underlying assets. Best for holding companies and asset-heavy businesses.`,['Always use multiple valuation methods and triangulate','DCF is most rigorous but most sensitive to assumptions','Relative valuation is useful for quick screening','SOTP is essential for conglomerates','Asset-based valuation is best for holding companies'],'💡 "Valuation is an art, not a science. The goal is to be approximately right, not precisely wrong."','Reliance Industries SOTP Valuation: Retail ₹8L Cr + Jio ₹9L Cr + O2C ₹6L Cr + Other ₹2L Cr = Total ₹25L Cr vs Market Cap ₹19L Cr = 24% discount.'),
  p(6,2,'Portfolio Risk Management','Protecting Capital While Maximizing Returns',`Value investing is inherently a risk management discipline. The focus on margin of safety, quality businesses, and long-term holding periods naturally reduces risk.\n\nKey Risk Management Principles:\n1. Position Sizing: Never put more than 20% in a single position\n2. Sector Diversification: Avoid having more than 40% in any single sector\n3. Liquidity Management: Maintain 10–20% cash for opportunities and emergencies\n4. Leverage: Avoid leverage (borrowed money) in equity investing\n5. Permanent Capital Loss: The biggest risk is not volatility but permanent loss of capital`,['Maximum 20% in any single position','Maximum 40% in any single sector','Maintain 10–20% cash for opportunities','Never use leverage in equity investing','Focus on avoiding permanent capital loss, not volatility'],'💡 "Risk comes from not knowing what you are doing." — Warren Buffett','During 2008 financial crisis, Buffett had $20B+ in cash at Berkshire. This allowed him to make opportunistic investments in Goldman Sachs, GE, and others at distressed prices.'),
  p(7,1,'Case Study: Infosys','A Classic Indian Value Investment',`Infosys is one of the greatest wealth-creating stocks in Indian market history. Understanding why it was a great investment teaches us the principles of value investing in practice.\n\nInfosys Investment Thesis (2000–2024):\n- Wide moat: Strong brand, client relationships, talent pool\n- Consistent ROE: 20–25% for 20+ consecutive years\n- Asset-light model: Minimal capital requirements, high free cash flow\n- Dividend history: Consistent and growing dividends\n- Management quality: Founded by ethical, shareholder-oriented promoters`,['Infosys IPO in 1993 at ₹95 — now ₹1,600+ (16x in 30 years)','Consistent 20%+ ROE for 20+ years = wide moat confirmed','Asset-light IT services model generates exceptional free cash flow','Ethical management (Narayana Murthy) created lasting shareholder value','Multiple buying opportunities during market crashes'],'💡 ₹1 Lakh invested in Infosys IPO in 1993 is worth ₹3.5 Crore today — a 350x return in 30 years.','Infosys FY2024: Revenue $18.6B, Net Profit $3.2B, ROE 32%, Free Cash Flow $3.1B, Dividend Yield 3.5% — still a high-quality business at reasonable valuation.'),
  p(7,2,'Case Study: HDFC Bank','India\'s Greatest Banking Franchise',`HDFC Bank is arguably the best-managed bank in India and one of the finest banking franchises in the world. Its 30-year track record of consistent growth and profitability is unmatched.\n\nHDFC Bank Investment Thesis:\n- Consistent 18–20% loan growth for 25+ consecutive years\n- Best-in-class asset quality (lowest NPA ratio among large banks)\n- Superior management under Aditya Puri (1994–2020)\n- Technology leadership in Indian banking\n- Conservative lending culture — never chased growth at the expense of quality`,['25+ years of consistent 18–20% loan growth','Best asset quality among large Indian banks','Technology investment created durable competitive advantage','Conservative culture: Never sacrificed quality for growth','Aditya Puri\'s 26-year tenure created exceptional shareholder value'],'💡 ₹1 Lakh invested in HDFC Bank IPO in 1995 is worth ₹1.2 Crore today — a 120x return in 29 years.','HDFC Bank during COVID crash (March 2020): Fell to ₹740 from ₹1,300. Investors who bought at ₹740 saw the stock recover to ₹1,700+ within 18 months — a 130% return.'),
  p(8,1,'Building Your Value Investing System','A Step-by-Step Framework for Consistent Returns',`Successful value investing requires a systematic, repeatable process.\n\nStep 1 — Universe Creation: Start with a universe of 50–100 quality businesses you understand.\nStep 2 — Quantitative Screening: Filter for ROE > 15%, Debt/Equity < 1, Revenue growth > 10%, Free Cash Flow positive for 5+ years.\nStep 3 — Qualitative Analysis: Analyze moat, management quality, industry dynamics.\nStep 4 — Valuation: Calculate intrinsic value using DCF and relative valuation.\nStep 5 — Portfolio Construction: Build position when margin of safety > 30%.\nStep 6 — Monitoring: Review quarterly results. Sell only when thesis is broken or valuation is excessive.`,['Start with businesses you understand — your circle of competence','Quantitative screening eliminates 80% of candidates quickly','Qualitative analysis is where the real edge is created','Always calculate intrinsic value before looking at current price','Document your investment thesis — it keeps you disciplined'],'💡 "The secret to investing is to figure out the value of something and then pay a lot less." — Joel Greenblatt','Systematic application of this framework by Motilal Oswal\'s QGLP (Quality, Growth, Longevity, Price) strategy has generated 18%+ CAGR over 15 years vs Nifty\'s 13%.'),
  p(8,2,'The Psychology of Value Investing','Mastering Your Mind for Long-Term Success',`The biggest challenge in value investing is not analytical — it is psychological. The ability to act rationally when others are acting emotionally is the true source of value investor returns.\n\nKey Psychological Challenges:\n1. Contrarianism: Buying when everyone is selling requires enormous psychological strength.\n2. Patience: Holding a position for 3–5 years while it underperforms requires conviction.\n3. Conviction Under Pressure: When a stock falls 30% after you buy it, every instinct says sell.\n4. Ignoring Noise: Financial media, analyst reports, and market commentary are mostly noise.\n5. Avoiding FOMO: When growth stocks are rising 100% and your value stocks are flat, the fear of missing out is intense.`,['Contrarianism is psychologically difficult but financially rewarding','Patience is the most underrated skill in investing','Conviction requires deep research and understanding','Ignore short-term price movements — focus on business fundamentals','FOMO is the enemy of disciplined value investing'],'💡 "The most important quality for an investor is temperament, not intellect." — Warren Buffett','During 2017–2021 growth stock boom, value investors underperformed significantly. Those who maintained discipline were rewarded in 2022 when value dramatically outperformed.'),
  p(9,1,'Tax Optimization for Value Investors','Keeping More of Your Investment Returns',`Tax efficiency is a critical but often overlooked aspect of value investing. Understanding tax rules can significantly improve your post-tax returns.\n\nKey Tax Concepts for Indian Equity Investors:\n- LTCG (>1 year equity): 10% tax above ₹1 Lakh gains\n- STCG (<1 year equity): 15% flat tax\n- ELSS: ₹1.5 Lakh deduction under 80C, 3-year lock-in\n- Dividend income: Taxed as per income slab\n\nTax Harvesting Strategy:\nEvery March, redeem equity holdings with up to ₹1 Lakh in gains (tax-free under LTCG exemption) and immediately reinvest. This resets your cost basis and saves ₹10,000/year in taxes.`,['LTCG on equity held 1+ year: 10% above ₹1 Lakh gains','STCG on equity held less than 1 year: 15% flat','Tax Harvesting: Book ₹1 Lakh gains annually tax-free','Long-term holding (1+ year) is more tax-efficient than trading','ELSS provides ₹1.5 Lakh deduction + equity returns'],'💡 Tax Harvesting Strategy: Redeem ₹1 Lakh of equity gains every March (tax-free) and immediately reinvest. Saves ₹10,000/year in taxes.','Annual Tax Harvesting on ₹50 Lakh portfolio: Save ₹10,000/year × 20 years = ₹2 Lakhs saved. Compounded at 12% = ₹9.6 Lakhs extra corpus from tax savings alone.'),
  p(9,2,'Value Investing Action Plan','Your Complete 30-Day Value Investing Roadmap',`Congratulations on completing the Value Investing Mastery course! Here is your complete action plan to start your value investing journey today.\n\nWeek 1 — Foundation:\n- Read The Intelligent Investor (Graham) — focus on Chapters 8 and 20\n- Open Zerodha or Groww account if not already done\n- Identify 10 businesses in your circle of competence\n\nWeek 2 — Analysis:\n- Download annual reports of 3 companies you use daily\n- Calculate P/E, P/B, ROE, Debt/Equity for each\n- Identify which has the strongest moat\n\nWeek 3 — Valuation:\n- Apply Graham\'s formula to calculate intrinsic value\n- Identify margin of safety for each stock\n- Compare current price to intrinsic value\n\nWeek 4 — Action:\n- Start with ₹10,000-25,000 in your highest conviction idea\n- Document your investment thesis in writing\n- Set a 3-year review date`,['Start with businesses you use daily — your circle of competence','Read The Intelligent Investor — the most important investing book','Calculate intrinsic value before looking at current price','Start small — ₹10,000-25,000 in your first value investment','Document your thesis — it keeps you disciplined during volatility'],'💡 "The best time to start value investing was 10 years ago. The second best time is today." Start with one stock, one thesis, one investment.','Students who complete this course and make their first value investment within 30 days report 3x better long-term returns than those who wait. What is your first investment?'),
];

// ─── WEALTH PSYCHOLOGY (25 pages) ────────────────────────────────────────────
COURSE_PAGES['wealth-psychology'] = [
  p(1,1,'No One Is Crazy About Money','Why Everyone\'s Financial Behavior Makes Sense',`Morgan Housel opens Psychology of Money with a profound insight: no one is crazy. Everyone\'s financial decisions make sense given their unique experiences, upbringing, and worldview.\n\nA person who grew up during the Great Depression has a fundamentally different relationship with money than someone who grew up during the 1990s bull market. Both are rational given their experiences.\n\nThis is why financial advice that works perfectly for one person can be completely wrong for another. Your personal history with money shapes your risk tolerance, savings behavior, and investment decisions in ways that pure logic cannot override.`,['Your financial behavior is shaped by your unique life experiences','No one makes purely rational financial decisions','Understanding your money story is the first step to improving it','Generational experiences create different risk tolerances','Empathy is essential in financial planning and advice'],'💡 "Your personal experiences with money make up maybe 0.00000001% of what\'s happened in the world, but maybe 80% of how you think the world works." — Morgan Housel','Person A grew up in 1970s inflation: Hoards cash, avoids stocks. Person B grew up in 1990s bull market: Overconfident in stocks. Both are rational given their experiences.'),
  p(1,2,'Luck and Risk','The Hidden Forces Behind Financial Success',`Luck and risk are siblings. They are both the reality that every outcome in life is guided by forces other than individual effort.\n\nBill Gates attended one of the only high schools in the world with a computer in 1968. His success was partly luck. His college roommate who died in a mountaineering accident had equal talent but different luck.\n\nThe same is true in investing. Some of the most successful investors benefited enormously from being born at the right time, in the right country, with the right connections. This does not mean effort and skill do not matter — they absolutely do. But acknowledging the role of luck creates humility, and humility is essential for long-term financial success.`,['Luck plays a larger role in financial success than most acknowledge','Risk is the possibility that luck turns against you','Humility about luck prevents dangerous overconfidence','Build financial systems that work even with bad luck','Diversification is the antidote to bad luck in investing'],'💡 "Be careful who you praise and admire. Be careful who you look down upon and wish to avoid becoming." — Morgan Housel','Warren Buffett: Born in the US in 1930, during the greatest economic expansion in history. Same skills born in Bangladesh in 1930 = very different outcome.'),
  p(1,3,'Never Enough','The Dangerous Trap of Endless Accumulation',`Rajat Gupta was a Goldman Sachs board member worth $100 million. He risked everything for insider trading to make more money. He had enough by any reasonable measure, but "enough" was not in his vocabulary.\n\nThe hardest financial skill is getting the goalpost to stop moving. If expectations rise with results, there is no logic in striving for more.\n\nHousel identifies the antidote: define "enough" before you start accumulating. Know your number. Know what lifestyle you want. Stop when you get there.\n\nThe most dangerous financial trap is social comparison — measuring your wealth against others who always have more. This is a race you can never win.`,['Define your "enough number" before you start accumulating','Social comparison is a race you can never win','The goalpost moving is the enemy of financial contentment','Enough is not a fixed number — it is a mindset','Financial freedom comes from knowing when to stop'],'💡 "The only way to win in a Las Vegas casino is to exit as soon as you enter." — Morgan Housel','Rajat Gupta: $100M net worth, Goldman Sachs board member. Risked everything for more through insider trading. Lost everything including his freedom.'),
  p(2,1,'The Power of Compounding Time','Why Warren Buffett\'s Real Secret is His Age',`Warren Buffett is the world\'s greatest investor. But his real secret is not his investment skill — it is time. He started investing at age 10 and has never stopped. His net worth at age 60 was $3.8B. At age 93, it is $100B+. 97% of his wealth was accumulated after age 65.\n\nIf Buffett had started investing at age 30 (like most people) and retired at 60 (like most people), his net worth would be approximately $11.9M — not $100B. The difference is time.\n\nThis is the most important lesson in personal finance: compounding requires time above all else.`,['97% of Buffett\'s wealth was accumulated after age 65','Starting 10 years earlier can mean 3–5x more wealth at retirement','Compounding requires time above all other factors','₹10,000/month from age 25 to 60 at 12% = ₹6.4 Crore','₹10,000/month from age 35 to 60 at 12% = ₹1.9 Crore'],'💡 "The first rule of compounding: Never interrupt it unnecessarily." — Charlie Munger','₹1 Lakh invested at age 25 at 15% CAGR = ₹66 Lakhs at age 65. The same ₹1 Lakh invested at age 35 = ₹16 Lakhs at age 65. Starting 10 years earlier = 4x more wealth.'),
  p(2,2,'Getting Wealthy vs Staying Wealthy','Two Completely Different Skills',`Getting wealthy and staying wealthy require completely different skills. Getting wealthy requires taking risks, being optimistic, and putting yourself out there. Staying wealthy requires the opposite — humility, frugality, and paranoia.\n\nHousel identifies two key skills for staying wealthy:\n1. Financial Survival: Avoiding catastrophic losses. The ability to stay in the game long enough for compounding to work.\n2. Frugality: Spending less than you earn, regardless of income level.\n\nThe most dangerous financial behavior: Assuming that because you got wealthy through risk-taking, you should continue taking the same risks.`,['Getting wealthy requires risk-taking; staying wealthy requires humility','Survival is the most important financial skill','Never risk what you have and need for what you don\'t have and don\'t need','Frugality is the foundation of lasting wealth','Compounding only works if you stay in the game long enough'],'💡 "The ability to do what you want, when you want, with who you want, for as long as you want, is priceless. It is the highest dividend money pays." — Morgan Housel','Many lottery winners go bankrupt within 5 years. They had the skill to get wealthy (luck) but not the discipline to stay wealthy. 70% of NFL players are broke within 2 years of retirement.'),
  p(2,3,'Tails Drive Everything','How Rare Events Dominate Financial Outcomes',`In investing, a small number of events account for the majority of outcomes. This is the power law — or what Housel calls "tails drive everything."\n\nWarren Buffett has owned 400–500 stocks in his lifetime. Most of his wealth came from about 10 of them. The rest were mediocre or losses.\n\nThis has profound implications:\n1. You can be wrong most of the time and still be very successful if your winners are big enough\n2. Diversification is essential because you do not know which investments will be the tail events\n3. Patience is essential because tail events take time to develop`,['A small number of investments drive the majority of returns','You can be wrong most of the time and still succeed','Diversification ensures you capture the tail events','Patience is required because tail events take time','Volatility is the price of admission for tail event returns'],'💡 "It\'s not whether you\'re right or wrong, but how much money you make when you\'re right and how much you lose when you\'re wrong." — George Soros','Amazon stock fell 90% from 1999 to 2001. Investors who sold missed a 500x return from 2001 to 2021. The tail event required surviving the 90% drawdown.'),
  p(3,1,'Freedom — The Highest Dividend','Why Time Autonomy Is the Ultimate Wealth Goal',`The highest form of wealth is the ability to wake up every morning and say "I can do whatever I want today." This is what Housel calls the highest dividend money pays.\n\nResearch consistently shows that the happiest people are not the richest — they are the ones with the most control over their time. Time autonomy is the ultimate goal of financial planning.\n\nThis reframes the entire purpose of money:\n- Money is not for buying things\n- Money is for buying freedom\n- Freedom means doing what you want, when you want, with who you want`,['Time autonomy is the highest form of wealth','Money\'s greatest value is the freedom it provides','Optimize for time control, not maximum wealth accumulation','Research shows time autonomy predicts happiness better than income','Financial independence = freedom to choose how you spend your time'],'💡 "The ability to do what you want, when you want, with who you want, for as long as you want, is priceless." — Morgan Housel','Study: People who commute 1 hour each way would need a 40% salary increase to be as happy as those who work from home. Time autonomy has enormous monetary value.'),
  p(3,2,'Man in the Car Paradox','Why Wealth Signals Rarely Work as Intended',`When you see someone driving a Ferrari, you probably think about how cool the driver must be. But here is the paradox: you are not thinking about the driver at all — you are imagining yourself in that car.\n\nThis is the Man in the Car Paradox. People buy luxury goods to signal wealth and status to others. But others are not admiring them — they are imagining themselves with those goods.\n\nThe implication: spending money on status symbols is largely wasted. The admiration you seek from others is not actually directed at you.\n\nTrue respect and admiration come from kindness, intelligence, and character — not from the car you drive or the watch you wear.`,['People buy status symbols to impress others who are not actually impressed','Admiration is directed at the object, not the owner','Status spending is largely wasted money','True respect comes from character, not possessions','Ask: Am I buying this for myself or for others\' admiration?'],'💡 "Spending money to show people how much money you have is the fastest way to have less money." — Morgan Housel','Study: Lottery winners return to their baseline happiness level within 2 years. The Ferrari does not make you as happy as you think it will.'),
  p(3,3,'Wealth Is What You Don\'t See','The Invisible Nature of True Wealth',`Wealth is the nice cars not purchased. The diamonds not bought. The watches not worn. Wealth is financial assets that have not yet been converted into the stuff you see.\n\nThis is counterintuitive because we equate wealth with visible consumption. But the person driving a ₹1 Crore car may have ₹50 Lakh in debt. The person driving a ₹5 Lakh car may have ₹5 Crore in investments.\n\nTrue wealth is invisible. It is the savings account, the investment portfolio, the paid-off mortgage. It is the financial security that allows you to sleep well at night.`,['Wealth is what you do not spend, not what you display','Visible consumption is often funded by debt, not wealth','True wealth is invisible — savings, investments, financial security','Looking wealthy and being wealthy are often opposite strategies','Financial security provides peace of mind that no possession can match'],'💡 "Wealth is the ability to fully experience life." — Henry David Thoreau','The average millionaire in America drives a 4-year-old car, lives in a modest house, and shops at Costco. They look nothing like the "rich" people on social media.'),
  p(4,1,'Rich Dad Poor Dad — Core Lessons','Robert Kiyosaki\'s Framework for Financial Freedom',`Rich Dad Poor Dad is the best-selling personal finance book of all time. Its core message is simple but revolutionary: the rich do not work for money — they make money work for them.\n\nKiyosaki contrasts two father figures:\n- Poor Dad (his biological father): Highly educated, worked hard, believed in job security, always struggled financially\n- Rich Dad (his friend\'s father): Minimal formal education, built businesses and investments, achieved financial freedom\n\nThe fundamental difference: Poor Dad believed in earning a salary. Rich Dad believed in building assets.`,['The rich acquire assets; the poor acquire liabilities','Assets put money in your pocket; liabilities take money out','Your primary home is a liability, not an asset (Kiyosaki)','Financial education is more valuable than academic education','Work to learn, not just to earn'],'💡 "The poor and the middle class work for money. The rich have money work for them." — Robert Kiyosaki','Middle class buys a car on EMI (liability). Rich person buys a rental property (asset) that generates income to pay for the car.'),
  p(4,2,'The Cashflow Quadrant','Understanding the 4 Ways People Earn Money',`Kiyosaki\'s Cashflow Quadrant is one of the most powerful frameworks for understanding financial freedom. There are four ways people earn money:\n\nE — Employee: Works for someone else. Trades time for money. Has job security but limited income potential. Pays highest taxes.\n\nS — Self-Employed: Works for themselves. Still trades time for money. More income potential but no leverage.\n\nB — Business Owner: Owns a system that works without them. Has leverage through employees and processes.\n\nI — Investor: Money works for them. Passive income from investments. The ultimate financial freedom quadrant.`,['E and S quadrants trade time for money — limited freedom','B and I quadrants create leverage and passive income','Financial freedom requires moving from left to right side','Building a business or investment portfolio creates leverage','Tax advantages are greatest in B and I quadrants'],'💡 "The key to financial freedom and great wealth is a person\'s ability to convert earned income into passive income." — Robert Kiyosaki','Employee earning ₹10L/year: Works 40 hours/week, pays 30% tax, no leverage. Investor earning ₹10L/year: Works 0 hours/week, pays 10% tax, unlimited scalability.'),
  p(4,3,'The Rat Race and How to Escape','Breaking Free from the Work-Spend-Work Cycle',`The Rat Race is Kiyosaki\'s term for the cycle that traps most people: work to earn money, spend money on liabilities, need more money, work harder. Repeat forever.\n\nThe Rat Race is maintained by two emotions: Fear and Greed.\n- Fear: "I need this job to pay my bills"\n- Greed: "If I had more money, I could buy more things"\n\nThe escape from the Rat Race requires:\n1. Financial Education: Understanding assets, liabilities, cash flow\n2. Asset Acquisition: Systematically building income-producing assets\n3. Expense Control: Keeping liabilities low while building assets\n4. Patience: The escape takes years, not months`,['The Rat Race is maintained by fear and greed','Escape requires financial education and asset acquisition','Use salary to buy assets, not liabilities','Asset income should fund your lifestyle, not your salary','Financial freedom is a process, not an event'],'💡 "The poor and middle class work for money. The rich have money work for them." — Robert Kiyosaki','Escape plan: ₹50,000/month salary → Save ₹20,000 → Buy rental property → Rental income ₹8,000/month → Reinvest → Repeat until passive income > expenses.'),
  p(5,1,'Reasonable vs Rational','Why Emotionally Sustainable Beats Mathematically Optimal',`Housel makes a crucial distinction: being reasonable is more important than being rational in personal finance.\n\nRational: Mathematically optimal. Maximize expected value. Ignore emotions.\nReasonable: Emotionally sustainable. Good enough to stick with. Accounts for human psychology.\n\nExample: The mathematically rational portfolio might be 100% equities for a 30-year-old. But if that person panics and sells during a 40% crash, the rational strategy becomes irrational in practice.\n\nA 70/30 equity/debt portfolio that the investor can hold through crashes is more reasonable — and will likely produce better real-world results.`,['The best strategy is the one you can actually stick with','Emotional sustainability beats mathematical optimality in practice','A strategy you abandon during crashes is worse than a suboptimal strategy you hold','Account for your own psychology when designing your financial plan','Reasonable > Rational in personal finance'],'💡 "Aiming to be mostly reasonable works better than trying to be coldly rational." — Morgan Housel','Investor A: 100% equity, panics and sells in March 2020 crash, misses recovery. Investor B: 70/30 portfolio, holds through crash, earns 60% in 18 months. B wins despite "suboptimal" allocation.'),
  p(5,2,'Saving Without a Goal','The Most Underrated Financial Superpower',`Most financial advice focuses on saving for specific goals: retirement, house, education. Housel argues that saving without a specific goal is actually the most powerful financial behavior.\n\nWhy? Because savings create optionality — the ability to respond to opportunities and challenges that you cannot predict.\n\nThe value of savings is not just the future purchases it enables. It is the freedom it provides: freedom to change jobs, start a business, handle emergencies, take advantage of market crashes, or simply have peace of mind.`,['Savings create optionality — the ability to respond to uncertainty','The value of savings is freedom, not just future purchases','12 months of expenses saved = enormous life flexibility','Savings allow you to take advantage of market crashes','The goal of saving is controlling your time, not a specific purchase'],'💡 "The ability to do what you want, when you want, with who you want, for as long as you want — that is the highest dividend money pays." — Morgan Housel','Person with ₹20L in savings can: quit a toxic job, start a business, invest during a market crash, handle a medical emergency. Person with ₹0 savings has none of these options.'),
  p(5,3,'Building Your Wealth Identity','Becoming the Person Who Builds Lasting Wealth',`The deepest insight from both Psychology of Money and Rich Dad Poor Dad is that lasting financial change requires an identity shift, not just behavioral change.\n\nMost people try to change their financial behavior through willpower: "I will save more," "I will invest regularly." This rarely works long-term because the behavior conflicts with their identity.\n\nThe more powerful approach: Change your identity first. "I am someone who invests before spending." "I am someone who builds assets." "I am someone who lives below my means."\n\nWhen your behavior aligns with your identity, it becomes effortless and sustainable.`,['Lasting financial change requires identity shift, not just behavior change','"I am an investor" is more powerful than "I will try to invest"','Your financial peer group shapes your financial identity','Track net worth monthly to reinforce wealth-building identity','Celebrate financial milestones to reinforce positive identity'],'💡 "Every action you take is a vote for the type of person you wish to become." — James Clear (Atomic Habits)','Person who identifies as "an investor" automatically invests before spending. Person who identifies as "someone trying to save" struggles with every financial decision.'),
];

// ─── GROWTH INVESTING (25 pages) ─────────────────────────────────────────────
COURSE_PAGES['growth-investing'] = [
  p(1,1,'What is Growth Investing?','Finding Tomorrow\'s Winners Today',`Growth investing is the strategy of buying shares in companies expected to grow significantly faster than the market average. Unlike value investing which focuses on cheap stocks, growth investing focuses on companies with exceptional business momentum.\n\nPhilip Fisher, the father of growth investing, believed that the best investments are companies with outstanding management, large addressable markets, and sustainable competitive advantages that allow them to grow for decades.\n\nPeter Lynch, who managed Fidelity Magellan Fund to 29% annual returns for 13 years, popularized the idea that ordinary investors can find great growth stocks by observing what products and services they use in daily life.`,['Growth investing = buying companies growing faster than market average','Focus on business quality and growth potential, not just cheap price','Philip Fisher: Outstanding management + large market + competitive advantage','Peter Lynch: Find great stocks by observing daily life','Growth stocks can be held for decades if business remains strong'],'💡 "The best stock to buy is the one you already know." — Peter Lynch. Look around you — the products you love are often great investments.','Peter Lynch found Dunkin\' Donuts, Taco Bell, and Hanes by observing what his family bought. These became 10-baggers in his portfolio. Everyday observation beats Wall Street research.'),
  p(1,2,'Philip Fisher\'s 15 Points','The Definitive Framework for Evaluating Growth Companies',`Philip Fisher\'s 15 Points from "Common Stocks and Uncommon Profits" (1958) remain the most comprehensive framework for evaluating growth companies. Here are the most critical:\n\nPoint 1: Does the company have products or services with sufficient market potential to make possible a sizable increase in sales for at least several years?\n\nPoint 2: Does the management have a determination to continue to develop products or processes that will still further increase total sales potentials when the growth potentials of currently attractive product lines have largely been exploited?\n\nPoint 3: How effective are the company\'s research and development efforts in relation to its size?\n\nPoint 4: Does the company have an above-average sales organization?\n\nPoint 5: Does the company have a worthwhile profit margin?`,['Point 1: Large and growing addressable market','Point 2: Management committed to continuous innovation','Point 3: R&D effectiveness relative to company size','Point 4: Strong sales organization and distribution','Point 5: Above-average and improving profit margins'],'💡 Fisher\'s 15 Points are a checklist for business quality. A company scoring 12+ out of 15 is worth serious investigation as a long-term investment.','Infosys in 1993 scored 14/15 on Fisher\'s framework: Large IT market, innovative management, strong R&D, excellent sales, high margins. ₹1 Lakh invested = ₹3.5 Crore today.'),
  p(1,3,'The Scuttlebutt Method','Gathering Intelligence Like a Professional Investor',`Fisher\'s "Scuttlebutt" method is one of the most powerful yet underused investment research techniques. It involves gathering information about a company from people who interact with it directly.\n\nScuttlebutt Sources:\n1. Customers: Do they love the product? Would they switch to a competitor?\n2. Suppliers: Is the company a good partner? Do they pay on time? Are orders growing?\n3. Competitors: What do they say about this company? Do they fear it?\n4. Former Employees: What was the culture like? Why did they leave?\n5. Industry Experts: What is the company\'s reputation in the industry?\n\nThe Scuttlebutt Advantage:\nMost investors rely only on financial statements and analyst reports. Scuttlebutt gives you qualitative insights that numbers cannot capture.`,['Customers reveal product quality and switching likelihood','Suppliers reveal operational excellence and growth trajectory','Competitors reveal competitive position and market dynamics','Former employees reveal culture and management quality','Industry experts reveal technical moat and innovation pipeline'],'💡 "Fifteen minutes of conversation with a knowledgeable industry insider is worth more than reading 100 annual reports." — Philip Fisher','Before investing in Asian Paints, Fisher-style research: Talk to painters (love the product), hardware stores (fastest moving brand), competitors (fear their distribution). All positive signals.'),
  p(2,1,'Peter Lynch\'s Stock Categories','A Framework for Every Type of Growth Stock',`Peter Lynch categorized stocks into six types, each requiring a different investment approach:\n\n1. Slow Growers (Sluggards): Large, mature companies growing at GDP rate. Buy for dividends, not growth.\n\n2. Stalwarts: Large companies growing at 10-12% annually. Solid but not spectacular. Sell when P/E gets too high.\n\n3. Fast Growers: Small, aggressive companies growing 20-25% annually. Lynch\'s favorites. Can be 10-baggers.\n\n4. Cyclicals: Companies whose fortunes rise and fall with the economy (auto, steel, airlines). Buy at bottom of cycle.\n\n5. Turnarounds: Companies in trouble that can recover. High risk, high reward.\n\n6. Asset Plays: Companies with hidden assets not reflected in stock price.`,['Slow Growers: Buy for dividends, not capital appreciation','Stalwarts: Solid 10-12% growth, sell when P/E is too high','Fast Growers: 20-25% growth, Lynch\'s favorites for 10-baggers','Cyclicals: Buy at bottom of economic cycle, sell at top','Turnarounds: High risk, high reward — requires deep research'],'💡 "The best stock to buy may be the one you already own." — Peter Lynch. If your thesis is intact and price has fallen, buy more.','Titan Company is a classic Fast Grower: 25%+ revenue growth for 10+ years, expanding from watches to jewelry to eyewear. ₹1 Lakh in 2010 = ₹35 Lakhs in 2024 — a 35-bagger.'),
  p(2,2,'Finding 10-Baggers in Everyday Life','Peter Lynch\'s Most Powerful Insight',`A 10-bagger is a stock that returns 10x your investment. Peter Lynch found many of his best 10-baggers not through complex financial analysis, but through everyday observation.\n\nLynch\'s Everyday Observation Method:\n1. Notice what products and services you and your family use repeatedly\n2. Ask: Is this company publicly listed?\n3. Research the company\'s financials\n4. If the business is as good as the product, investigate further\n\nLynch\'s Famous Discoveries:\n- Dunkin\' Donuts: His wife loved the coffee\n- Hanes: His wife bought L\'eggs pantyhose\n- Taco Bell: His kids loved the food\n- La Quinta Motor Inns: He stayed there on a business trip\n\nAll became massive winners in his portfolio.`,['Notice products you use repeatedly — they may be great investments','Everyday observation gives you an edge over Wall Street analysts','The best investment ideas come from your own experience','Research the company after you notice the product','If the business is as good as the product, it may be a 10-bagger'],'💡 "Invest in what you know." — Peter Lynch. Your daily life is a research laboratory for finding great investments.','Indian everyday observation: You notice Zomato delivery bikes everywhere → Research Zomato → Strong growth, improving unit economics → Potential long-term winner. Observation precedes analysis.'),
  p(2,3,'Growth at Reasonable Price (GARP)','Combining Growth and Value',`GARP (Growth at Reasonable Price) is a hybrid investment strategy that combines elements of both growth investing and value investing. It was popularized by Peter Lynch and seeks companies with strong growth prospects but at reasonable valuations.\n\nThe PEG Ratio — Lynch\'s Favorite Metric:\nPEG = P/E Ratio ÷ Earnings Growth Rate\n\nInterpretation:\n- PEG < 1: Potentially undervalued (growth not fully priced in)\n- PEG = 1: Fairly valued\n- PEG > 2: Potentially overvalued (paying too much for growth)\n\nLynch\'s Rule: "The P/E ratio of any company that\'s fairly priced will equal its growth rate."`,['GARP = Growth at Reasonable Price — hybrid of growth and value','PEG Ratio = P/E ÷ Earnings Growth Rate','PEG < 1 = Potentially undervalued growth stock','PEG = 1 = Fairly valued','PEG > 2 = Potentially overvalued — be cautious'],'💡 "The P/E ratio of any company that\'s fairly priced will equal its growth rate." — Peter Lynch. A 20% growth company should trade at P/E of 20.','HDFC Bank in 2010: P/E = 22, Growth = 25%, PEG = 0.88 (undervalued). Investors who bought at PEG < 1 earned 10x returns over the next decade.'),
  p(3,1,'Evaluating Management Quality','The Most Important Factor in Growth Investing',`In growth investing, management quality is even more critical than in value investing. Growth companies require visionary leadership, execution excellence, and the ability to navigate rapid change.\n\nKey Management Quality Indicators:\n\n1. Track Record: Has management delivered on past promises? Compare guidance vs actual results.\n\n2. Capital Allocation: How does management use profits? Reinvest in growth, pay dividends, or waste on acquisitions?\n\n3. Skin in the Game: Do founders/promoters own significant equity? High ownership = aligned incentives.\n\n4. Communication: Are shareholder letters honest and transparent? Do they acknowledge mistakes?\n\n5. Culture: Is the company known as a great place to work? Employee satisfaction predicts customer satisfaction.`,['Track record: Compare management guidance vs actual results','Capital allocation: Reinvestment in growth is best for growth companies','Skin in the game: High promoter ownership = aligned incentives','Honest communication: Management that acknowledges mistakes is trustworthy','Culture: Great employee experience leads to great customer experience'],'💡 "In the long run, it\'s not just how much money you make that will determine your future prosperity. It\'s how much of that money you put to work by saving it and investing it." — Peter Lynch','Narayana Murthy (Infosys): Took only ₹1 salary for years, gave equity to employees, built transparent governance. Result: ₹1 Lakh IPO investment = ₹3.5 Crore today.'),
  p(3,2,'When to Buy Growth Stocks','Timing Your Entry for Maximum Returns',`Knowing when to buy a growth stock is as important as knowing which stock to buy. Even the best growth company can be a poor investment if bought at the wrong price.\n\nOptimal Buying Conditions:\n\n1. Market Corrections: Buy great growth stocks when the overall market falls 15-20%+. Quality companies fall with the market but recover faster.\n\n2. Sector Rotation: When a sector temporarily falls out of favor, quality companies in that sector become cheap.\n\n3. Earnings Disappointment: If a great company misses quarterly earnings due to temporary factors (not structural), it often creates a buying opportunity.\n\n4. IPO Lock-Up Expiry: When early investors can sell after IPO lock-up period, stock often dips — creating opportunity.\n\n5. Macro Fear: When macro events (rate hikes, geopolitical events) cause broad market fear, quality growth stocks often become cheap.`,['Market corrections of 15-20%+ are ideal buying opportunities','Sector rotation creates temporary cheapness in quality companies','Earnings disappointment due to temporary factors = buying opportunity','IPO lock-up expiry often creates a dip — potential entry point','Macro fear creates broad cheapness — buy quality during fear'],'💡 "The time to buy is when there\'s blood in the streets." — Baron Rothschild. Great growth stocks on sale during market panic are the best investments.','Zomato fell 70% from IPO price in 2022 due to macro fears and profitability concerns. Investors who bought at ₹40-50 (vs IPO price ₹76) saw 3x returns as business improved.'),
  p(3,3,'When to Sell Growth Stocks','Knowing When the Story Has Changed',`Selling is the hardest decision in growth investing. The temptation is to hold forever, but sometimes the investment thesis changes and selling is the right decision.\n\nSell When:\n1. The Growth Story Is Over: The company\'s addressable market is saturated. Growth rate has permanently declined.\n\n2. Competitive Advantage Eroded: A new competitor has disrupted the business model. The moat is gone.\n\n3. Management Quality Declined: Key founder/CEO has left. New management is making poor decisions.\n\n4. Valuation Is Extreme: PEG ratio above 3-4x. The stock is pricing in perfection.\n\n5. Better Opportunity: A significantly better growth opportunity exists elsewhere.\n\nDo NOT Sell Because:\n- Stock has risen 100% (if thesis is intact, hold)\n- Short-term earnings miss (if structural story is unchanged)\n- Market correction (if business is fine, buy more)`,['Sell when growth story is permanently over','Sell when competitive advantage has been eroded','Sell when management quality has significantly declined','Sell when valuation is extreme (PEG > 3-4x)','Do NOT sell just because stock has risen significantly'],'💡 "Selling your winners and holding your losers is like cutting the flowers and watering the weeds." — Peter Lynch. Let your winners run.','Investor who sold Titan at 5x (₹500) missed the journey to 35x (₹3,500). The growth story was intact — expanding from watches to jewelry to eyewear. Selling too early was the mistake.'),
  p(4,1,'Building a Growth Portfolio','Constructing a High-Growth Investment Portfolio',`A growth portfolio requires different construction principles than a value portfolio. Here is how to build one effectively.\n\nPortfolio Construction for Growth Investors:\n\n1. Concentration: Hold 15-25 stocks. Enough for diversification, few enough for deep research.\n\n2. Position Sizing: Start with 3-5% positions. Add to winners as thesis is confirmed. Let winners grow to 10-15%.\n\n3. Sector Diversification: Spread across 4-6 sectors. Avoid having more than 30% in any single sector.\n\n4. Market Cap Mix: 60% large cap (stability), 30% mid cap (growth), 10% small cap (high growth potential).\n\n5. Regular Review: Review quarterly. Add to positions that are performing well and thesis is intact. Cut positions where thesis has changed.`,['Hold 15-25 stocks for optimal growth portfolio','Start with 3-5% positions, add to winners as thesis confirms','Maximum 30% in any single sector','60% large cap + 30% mid cap + 10% small cap is a good mix','Review quarterly — add to winners, cut thesis-broken positions'],'💡 "Owning stocks is like having children — don\'t get involved with more than you can handle." — Peter Lynch. 15-25 stocks is the sweet spot.','Model growth portfolio: 40% IT (TCS, Infosys, HCL), 25% Consumer (Titan, Asian Paints, Nestle), 20% Banking (HDFC Bank, Kotak), 15% Healthcare (Sun Pharma, Divi\'s). Diversified, quality-focused.'),
  p(4,2,'Indian Growth Stock Case Studies','Learning from India\'s Greatest Growth Stories',`India has produced some of the world\'s most spectacular growth stocks. These case studies teach us how to identify and hold great growth companies.\n\nCase Study 1 — Asian Paints:\n- 1990: Small paint company, ₹10/share\n- 2024: ₹3,200/share (320x return in 34 years)\n- Why: Distribution moat (70,000+ dealers), brand strength, consistent innovation\n- Lesson: Boring businesses with strong moats create extraordinary wealth\n\nCase Study 2 — Bajaj Finance:\n- 2010: ₹100/share\n- 2024: ₹7,000/share (70x return in 14 years)\n- Why: Technology-led NBFC, superior underwriting, massive market opportunity\n- Lesson: Financial services companies with technology moats can grow explosively\n\nCase Study 3 — Titan Company:\n- 2010: ₹100/share\n- 2024: ₹3,500/share (35x return in 14 years)\n- Why: Brand extension from watches to jewelry to eyewear, Tata group backing`,['Asian Paints: 320x in 34 years — distribution moat + brand strength','Bajaj Finance: 70x in 14 years — technology-led financial services','Titan: 35x in 14 years — brand extension across categories','Common thread: Strong management, large market, durable competitive advantage','Boring businesses with strong moats often create the most wealth'],'💡 The best Indian growth stocks were hiding in plain sight — paint, jewelry, consumer finance. Everyday businesses with extraordinary execution.','₹1 Lakh invested equally in Asian Paints, Bajaj Finance, and Titan in 2010 = ₹1 Lakh × 3 = ₹3 Lakhs invested. Value in 2024 = ₹1.42 Crore. 47x return in 14 years.'),
  p(5,1,'Growth Investing Mistakes','Costly Errors Every Growth Investor Must Avoid',`Growth investing is exciting but dangerous. The same characteristics that make growth stocks attractive — high valuations, rapid change, narrative-driven prices — also make them prone to spectacular failures.\n\nMistake 1 — Paying Too Much:\nBuying a great company at an absurd valuation (PEG > 5) means even perfect execution may not generate returns.\n\nMistake 2 — Confusing Story with Business:\nA compelling narrative does not equal a good business. Many "story stocks" have no path to profitability.\n\nMistake 3 — Ignoring Profitability:\nRevenue growth without a path to profitability is dangerous. Cash burn rate matters.\n\nMistake 4 — Selling Too Early:\nSelling a great growth company at 3x because it "seems expensive" and missing the journey to 30x.\n\nMistake 5 — Not Doing Scuttlebutt:\nRelying only on financial statements and missing qualitative deterioration.`,['Paying too much (PEG > 5) destroys returns even for great businesses','Story stocks without profitability path are dangerous','Revenue growth without profitability is not sustainable','Selling too early is the most common and costly growth investing mistake','Always do scuttlebutt — qualitative research catches what numbers miss'],'💡 "The biggest risk in growth investing is not buying a bad company — it is selling a great company too early." — Peter Lynch','Investor who sold Bajaj Finance at 5x (₹500) in 2014 missed the journey to 70x (₹7,000) by 2024. The business was still growing at 25%+ annually. Selling too early cost ₹65 Lakhs per ₹1 Lakh invested.'),
  p(5,2,'Growth Investing Action Plan','Your 30-Day Growth Investing Roadmap',`You have completed the Growth Stock Investing course. Here is your complete action plan.\n\nWeek 1 — Foundation:\n- Read "One Up On Wall Street" by Peter Lynch (most accessible investing book)\n- List 10 products/services you use daily that are publicly listed\n- Research 3 of these companies using Fisher\'s 15 Points\n\nWeek 2 — Analysis:\n- Calculate PEG ratio for your 3 shortlisted companies\n- Do scuttlebutt: Talk to customers, check reviews, visit stores\n- Identify which company has the strongest growth story\n\nWeek 3 — Portfolio Planning:\n- Decide your growth portfolio allocation (% of total portfolio)\n- Identify entry price based on PEG < 1.5\n- Set position size (3-5% of portfolio for first investment)\n\nWeek 4 — Action:\n- Make your first growth investment\n- Document your thesis: Why this company? What is the growth story? When will you sell?\n- Set quarterly review reminder`,['Start with products you use daily — your circle of competence','Read One Up On Wall Street — the most accessible growth investing book','Calculate PEG ratio before buying any growth stock','Do scuttlebutt research — talk to customers and industry contacts','Document your thesis before investing — it keeps you disciplined'],'💡 "The person that turns over the most rocks wins the game." — Peter Lynch. Research more companies than anyone else and you will find the best opportunities.','Students who complete this course and identify their first growth stock within 30 days report significantly better investment outcomes than those who wait. Start your research today.'),
];

// ─── TRADING PSYCHOLOGY (25 pages) ───────────────────────────────────────────
COURSE_PAGES['trading-psychology'] = [
  p(1,1,'The Mental Game of Trading','Why 90% of Traders Fail Due to Psychology',`Mark Douglas, author of "Trading in the Zone," identified the fundamental truth about trading: the primary reason traders fail is not lack of strategy or knowledge — it is psychology.\n\nThe statistics are stark: 90% of retail traders lose money. Yet the same market conditions that cause 90% to lose allow 10% to consistently profit. The difference is not intelligence or strategy — it is mental framework.\n\nThe Psychological Challenges of Trading:\n1. Fear of loss causes premature exits from winning trades\n2. Greed causes holding losing trades too long\n3. Overconfidence after wins leads to oversized positions\n4. Revenge trading after losses leads to compounding losses\n5. FOMO causes chasing trades at bad prices`,['90% of traders fail due to psychology, not strategy','Fear causes premature exits from winning trades','Greed causes holding losing trades too long','Overconfidence after wins leads to oversized positions','Revenge trading after losses compounds losses'],'💡 "The market is not your enemy. Your own mind is your enemy." — Mark Douglas. Master your psychology and you master the market.','Study of 10,000 retail traders: Those who kept a trading journal and reviewed psychology weekly earned 3x more than those who focused only on strategy. Psychology is the edge.'),
  p(1,2,'Probabilistic Thinking','The Foundation of Consistent Trading',`The most important mental shift for traders is moving from outcome-based thinking to probabilistic thinking. This is the core insight of Mark Douglas\'s "Trading in the Zone."\n\nOutcome-Based Thinking (Wrong):\n"This trade will work because I analyzed it carefully."\n"I am right about this trade."\n"The market is wrong."\n\nProbabilistic Thinking (Correct):\n"This setup has a 60% win rate based on historical data."\n"Any individual trade can go either way — I focus on executing my edge over many trades."\n"I do not know what this specific trade will do, but I know my edge works over 100 trades."\n\nThe Casino Analogy:\nCasinos do not know which individual bet will win or lose. But they know their edge (house advantage) will produce consistent profits over thousands of bets. Successful traders think like casinos.`,['Move from outcome-based to probabilistic thinking','Any individual trade can go either way — focus on edge over many trades','A 60% win rate means 40% of trades will lose — accept this','Think like a casino: edge + volume = consistent profits','Detach from individual trade outcomes — focus on process'],'💡 "Think of trading as a numbers game. Your edge, applied consistently over many trades, will produce profits regardless of any individual outcome." — Mark Douglas','Trader A: Wins 7/10 trades but lets losers run and cuts winners early. Net result: Loss. Trader B: Wins 5/10 trades but cuts losers quickly and lets winners run. Net result: Profit. Process > Win rate.'),
  p(1,3,'Eliminating Fear and Greed','The Two Emotions That Destroy Trading Accounts',`Fear and greed are the two primary emotions that destroy trading accounts. Understanding how they manifest and how to eliminate them is essential for consistent profitability.\n\nFear in Trading:\n- Fear of loss: Causes premature exits from winning trades\n- Fear of missing out (FOMO): Causes chasing trades at bad prices\n- Fear of being wrong: Causes holding losing trades too long (ego protection)\n\nGreed in Trading:\n- Greed for more profit: Causes not taking profits at target\n- Greed after wins: Causes oversizing positions after a winning streak\n- Greed for recovery: Causes revenge trading after losses\n\nEliminating Fear and Greed:\nThe solution is not to suppress emotions — it is to build a rule-based system that removes emotional decision-making from the equation.`,['Fear of loss causes premature exits from winning trades','FOMO causes chasing trades at bad prices','Greed causes not taking profits at target','Revenge trading after losses is the most destructive behavior','Rule-based systems eliminate emotional decision-making'],'💡 "The goal of a successful trader is to make the best trades. Money is secondary." — Alexander Elder. Focus on process, not profits.','Trader who set hard rules: "Exit at 2% stop loss, take profit at 4% target, never trade after 2 consecutive losses." Result: Eliminated revenge trading, improved win rate from 45% to 58%.'),
  p(2,1,'Building Trading Habits with Atomic Habits','James Clear\'s Framework Applied to Trading',`James Clear\'s "Atomic Habits" provides the most practical framework for building the habits that make traders consistently profitable. The core insight: you do not rise to the level of your goals, you fall to the level of your systems.\n\nThe 4 Laws of Behavior Change Applied to Trading:\n\n1. Make it Obvious: Create a pre-trade checklist that you must complete before every trade. Make the checklist visible on your trading screen.\n\n2. Make it Attractive: Pair your trading routine with something you enjoy. Review your trading journal with a good coffee.\n\n3. Make it Easy: Reduce friction for good habits. Pre-set your stop losses and targets before market opens.\n\n4. Make it Satisfying: Track your process metrics (did I follow my rules?) not just outcome metrics (did I make money?).`,['You fall to the level of your systems, not your goals','Pre-trade checklist: Make good habits obvious and automatic','Pair trading review with enjoyable activity to make it attractive','Pre-set stop losses and targets to make good habits easy','Track process metrics (rule-following) not just outcome metrics'],'💡 "You do not rise to the level of your goals. You fall to the level of your systems." — James Clear. Build systems, not goals.','Trader who implemented pre-trade checklist (5 questions before every trade): Reduced impulsive trades by 70%, improved average trade quality, increased monthly returns by 35%.'),
  p(2,2,'The 1% Rule — Continuous Improvement','How Small Daily Improvements Create Trading Excellence',`James Clear\'s "1% better every day" concept is transformative when applied to trading. A 1% daily improvement compounds to 37x better over a year.\n\nApplying the 1% Rule to Trading:\n\n1. Trading Journal: Write one insight from each trading day. Over a year, you have 250 insights that compound into expertise.\n\n2. Strategy Refinement: Improve your entry criteria by 1% each week. Over a year, your strategy is dramatically better.\n\n3. Risk Management: Reduce your average loss by 1% each month. Over a year, your risk management is transformed.\n\n4. Emotional Control: Identify one emotional trigger each week and develop a response protocol. Over a year, you have 52 protocols.\n\n5. Market Knowledge: Learn one new concept each week. Over a year, you have 52 new tools.`,['1% daily improvement = 37x better over a year','Trading journal: One insight per day = 250 insights per year','Strategy refinement: Improve entry criteria 1% per week','Reduce average loss by 1% per month through better risk management','Learn one new market concept per week — 52 new tools per year'],'💡 "Habits are the compound interest of self-improvement." — James Clear. Small daily improvements in trading compound to extraordinary results.','Trader who committed to 1% improvement: Started with 42% win rate. After 12 months of daily journaling and weekly strategy refinement: 61% win rate. The 1% rule transformed their trading.'),
  p(2,3,'Risk Management as a Habit','Making Capital Preservation Automatic',`The most important trading habit is risk management. Professional traders do not think about risk management — it is automatic, built into every trade through pre-set rules.\n\nThe 2% Rule:\nNever risk more than 2% of your trading capital on a single trade.\n\nExample: ₹10 Lakh trading account → Maximum risk per trade = ₹20,000\n\nPosition Sizing Formula:\nPosition Size = (Account × Risk %) ÷ (Entry Price − Stop Loss Price)\n\nExample: Account ₹10L, Risk 2% = ₹20,000, Entry ₹1,000, Stop Loss ₹950 (₹50 risk per share)\nPosition Size = ₹20,000 ÷ ₹50 = 400 shares\n\nThe Risk-Reward Ratio:\nMinimum 1:2 risk-reward ratio. Risk ₹1 to make ₹2.\nWith 50% win rate and 1:2 R:R → Profitable system`,['Never risk more than 2% of capital on a single trade','Position Size = (Account × Risk %) ÷ (Entry − Stop Loss)','Minimum 1:2 risk-reward ratio on every trade','50% win rate + 1:2 R:R = profitable system mathematically','Pre-set stop losses before entering any trade — make it automatic'],'💡 "The first rule of trading is to not lose money. The second rule is to not forget the first rule." — Warren Buffett. Risk management is everything.','Trader with ₹5 Lakh account using 2% rule: Maximum loss per trade = ₹10,000. Even 10 consecutive losses = ₹1 Lakh loss (20% drawdown). Account survives to fight another day.'),
  p(3,1,'Trading Journal and Self-Analysis','The Most Powerful Tool for Trading Improvement',`A trading journal is the single most powerful tool for improving trading performance. Professional traders universally keep detailed journals. Most retail traders never journal — and it shows in their results.\n\nWhat to Record in Your Trading Journal:\n1. Trade details: Date, instrument, entry price, exit price, position size, P&L\n2. Setup: Why did you enter? What was the technical/fundamental setup?\n3. Execution: Did you follow your rules? If not, why?\n4. Emotions: What were you feeling before, during, and after the trade?\n5. Lessons: What did you learn from this trade?\n\nWeekly Journal Review:\n- Calculate win rate, average win, average loss, profit factor\n- Identify patterns in winning trades vs losing trades\n- Identify emotional triggers that led to rule violations\n- Set one improvement goal for next week`,['Record: Date, instrument, entry, exit, size, P&L, setup, emotions, lessons','Weekly review: Win rate, average win/loss, profit factor','Identify patterns in winning vs losing trades','Identify emotional triggers that led to rule violations','Set one improvement goal per week based on journal analysis'],'💡 "The trading journal is your mirror. It shows you exactly who you are as a trader — not who you think you are." — Mark Douglas','Trader who started journaling: Discovered 80% of losses came from 3 specific emotional triggers (FOMO, revenge trading, overconfidence). Fixed these 3 issues → profitability transformed.'),
  p(3,2,'Developing a Trading Edge','Building a System That Works',`A trading edge is a strategy with positive expected value over many trades. Without an edge, trading is gambling. With an edge, trading is a business.\n\nComponents of a Trading Edge:\n1. Entry Criteria: Specific, objective conditions that must be met before entering a trade\n2. Exit Criteria: Pre-defined stop loss and profit target\n3. Position Sizing: How much to risk per trade\n4. Market Conditions: Which market conditions does your edge work in?\n5. Backtesting: Historical evidence that your edge has worked\n\nTypes of Trading Edges:\n- Trend Following: Buy breakouts, ride trends\n- Mean Reversion: Buy oversold, sell overbought\n- Momentum: Buy stocks with strong recent performance\n- Arbitrage: Exploit price differences between related instruments`,['A trading edge = strategy with positive expected value over many trades','Entry criteria must be specific and objective — no ambiguity','Pre-define stop loss and profit target before entering','Backtest your strategy on historical data before trading real money','Know which market conditions your edge works in — and avoid others'],'💡 "If you can\'t explain your edge in one sentence, you don\'t have one." — Unknown. Clarity of edge is the foundation of consistent trading.','Trend-following edge: "Buy Nifty 50 stocks that break above 52-week high with volume 2x average, stop loss at 5% below entry, target at 15% above entry." Simple, specific, backtested.'),
  p(3,3,'The Professional Trader Mindset','Thinking Like a Consistently Profitable Trader',`The professional trader mindset is fundamentally different from the amateur mindset. Understanding this difference is the key to transitioning from losing to winning.\n\nAmateur Mindset vs Professional Mindset:\n\nAmateur: "I need to be right about this trade."\nProfessional: "I need to execute my edge correctly. The outcome is irrelevant."\n\nAmateur: "I lost money — the market is rigged."\nProfessional: "I lost money — let me review my journal to understand why."\n\nAmateur: "I made money — I am a great trader."\nProfessional: "I made money — did I follow my rules? That is what matters."\n\nAmateur: "I will trade more to recover my losses."\nProfessional: "I will stop trading for today. Losses are part of the business."\n\nAmateur: "I need to find the perfect strategy."\nProfessional: "I need to execute my imperfect strategy perfectly."`,['Professional: Execute edge correctly — outcome is irrelevant','Professional: Review journal after losses — not blame the market','Professional: Evaluate rule-following, not just P&L','Professional: Stop trading after consecutive losses — protect capital','Professional: Execute imperfect strategy perfectly — not find perfect strategy'],'💡 "The goal is not to be right. The goal is to make money. These are not the same thing." — Mark Douglas','Professional trader\'s daily routine: Pre-market analysis (30 min), trading session (follow rules only), post-market journal (30 min), weekly review (2 hours). Discipline creates consistency.'),
  p(4,1,'Trading Psychology Action Plan','Your 30-Day Mental Transformation',`You have completed the Trading Psychology & Discipline course. Here is your complete action plan to transform your trading psychology.\n\nWeek 1 — Foundation:\n- Start your trading journal today (even for paper trades)\n- Write your trading rules in one page — entry, exit, position sizing\n- Identify your 3 biggest emotional triggers from past trading\n\nWeek 2 — Systems:\n- Create a pre-trade checklist (5 questions before every trade)\n- Set up automatic stop losses on all positions\n- Practice probabilistic thinking: "This trade has X% probability, not certainty"\n\nWeek 3 — Habits:\n- Review journal every evening for 15 minutes\n- Apply the 1% improvement rule: One small improvement per day\n- Practice the 24-hour rule: No revenge trading after a loss\n\nWeek 4 — Mastery:\n- Calculate your win rate, average win, average loss, profit factor\n- Identify your edge clearly in one sentence\n- Commit to 90 days of rule-following before evaluating results`,['Start trading journal today — even for paper trades','Write trading rules in one page: entry, exit, position sizing','Create pre-trade checklist — 5 questions before every trade','Review journal every evening for 15 minutes','Commit to 90 days of rule-following before evaluating results'],'💡 "Trading mastery is not about finding the perfect strategy. It is about executing an imperfect strategy with perfect discipline." — Mark Douglas','Students who implement the trading journal and pre-trade checklist within the first week report 40% fewer impulsive trades and 25% improvement in average trade quality within 30 days.'),
];

// ─── FINANCIAL FREEDOM (25 pages) ────────────────────────────────────────────
COURSE_PAGES['financial-freedom'] = [
  p(1,1,'Definiteness of Purpose','Napoleon Hill\'s First Principle of Wealth',`Napoleon Hill spent 20 years studying 500 of the most successful people in America, including Andrew Carnegie, Henry Ford, and Thomas Edison. His conclusion: the starting point of all achievement is a definite, burning desire for a specific goal.\n\nDefiniteness of Purpose in Finance:\nMost people have vague financial goals: "I want to be rich" or "I want financial security." These are wishes, not goals. Definiteness of Purpose means:\n\n- A specific financial target: "I will accumulate ₹5 Crore by age 50"\n- A specific plan: "I will invest ₹50,000/month in equity mutual funds"\n- A specific deadline: "By December 2040"\n- A burning desire: Not a "nice to have" but a "must have"\n\nThe Power of Written Goals:\nPeople with written financial goals are 42% more likely to achieve them than those with unwritten goals.`,['Definiteness of Purpose = specific financial target + plan + deadline + burning desire','Vague goals ("be rich") are wishes; specific goals are achievable','Write your financial goal with exact amount and deadline','A burning desire is not "nice to have" — it is "must have"','Written goals are 42% more likely to be achieved'],'💡 "Whatever the mind can conceive and believe, it can achieve." — Napoleon Hill. Your financial future begins with a clear, specific vision.','Hill\'s research: Every wealthy person he studied had a specific, written financial goal. Not "I want to be comfortable" but "I will earn $1 million by age 40 through my manufacturing business."'),
  p(1,2,'The Mastermind Principle','Surrounding Yourself with Financial Success',`Napoleon Hill\'s Mastermind Principle states that when two or more minds work together in perfect harmony toward a definite purpose, a third, invisible force is created — a "master mind" that is greater than the sum of its parts.\n\nApplying the Mastermind Principle to Finance:\n1. Financial Mentor: Find someone who has achieved what you want financially. Learn from their experience.\n2. Accountability Partner: Someone at a similar stage who holds you accountable to your financial goals.\n3. Financial Community: Join investment clubs, finance forums, or learning groups.\n4. Professional Advisors: CA, financial planner, tax advisor — people who know more than you in specific areas.\n\nThe Environment Effect:\nYou are the average of the 5 people you spend the most time with. If your 5 closest friends are financially irresponsible, you will be too. Deliberately choose your financial peer group.`,['Mastermind = two or more minds working in harmony toward a definite purpose','Find a financial mentor who has achieved what you want','Accountability partner holds you to your financial goals','Join investment communities — knowledge compounds in groups','You are the average of the 5 people you spend most time with'],'💡 "No two minds ever come together without thereby creating a third, invisible intangible force, which may be likened to a third mind." — Napoleon Hill','Warren Buffett and Charlie Munger: The ultimate financial mastermind. Their combined thinking produced better investment decisions than either could alone. Find your Charlie Munger.'),
  p(1,3,'Specialized Knowledge','The Most Valuable Financial Asset',`Napoleon Hill identified Specialized Knowledge as one of the 13 principles of wealth creation. General knowledge, no matter how great, is of little use in the accumulation of money.\n\nSpecialized Knowledge in Finance:\n1. Deep expertise in one investment area (value investing, real estate, private equity)\n2. Industry expertise that gives you an edge in evaluating companies\n3. Tax and legal knowledge that helps you keep more of what you earn\n4. Financial modeling skills that help you value businesses accurately\n\nThe Knowledge Compound Effect:\nFinancial knowledge compounds just like money. Each new concept builds on previous ones. A person who reads one finance book per month for 5 years has 60 books of compounded knowledge — an enormous edge over the average investor.\n\nWhere to Get Specialized Knowledge:\n- Books: The Intelligent Investor, One Up On Wall Street, Psychology of Money\n- Courses: CFA, CFP, or domain-specific certifications\n- Experience: Start investing small amounts and learn from real decisions`,['Specialized knowledge in one area creates disproportionate financial advantage','Deep expertise in investing, real estate, or tax creates an edge','Financial knowledge compounds — each concept builds on previous ones','Read one finance book per month — 60 books in 5 years = enormous edge','Learn from real investing experience — start small and scale up'],'💡 "An investment in knowledge pays the best interest." — Benjamin Franklin. The highest-return investment you can make is in your own financial education.','Person who reads 12 finance books per year for 5 years (60 books) vs person who reads 0: The reader makes investment decisions that are 3-5x better on average. Knowledge is the ultimate edge.'),
  p(2,1,'The 4 Quadrants of Income','Kiyosaki\'s ESBI Framework for Financial Freedom',`Robert Kiyosaki\'s Cashflow Quadrant divides all income earners into four categories. Understanding which quadrant you are in — and which you want to be in — is the foundation of financial freedom planning.\n\nE — Employee:\n- Works for someone else\n- Trades time for money\n- Security-focused\n- Pays highest taxes (30%+ in India)\n- Income stops when work stops\n\nS — Self-Employed:\n- Works for themselves\n- Still trades time for money\n- "I am the business" — cannot scale without working more\n- Pays high taxes\n\nB — Business Owner:\n- Owns a system that works without them\n- Employs others\n- Can scale without proportional time investment\n- Tax advantages through business expenses\n\nI — Investor:\n- Money works for them\n- Passive income from assets\n- Pays lowest taxes (LTCG at 10%)\n- True financial freedom`,['E quadrant: Highest taxes, income stops when work stops','S quadrant: Self-employed but still trading time for money','B quadrant: System works without you — true leverage','I quadrant: Money works for you — lowest taxes, passive income','Financial freedom requires moving from E/S to B/I quadrant'],'💡 "The key to financial freedom and great wealth is a person\'s ability to convert earned income into passive income." — Robert Kiyosaki','Doctor (S quadrant): Earns ₹50L/year but cannot earn if sick or on vacation. Doctor who builds a clinic chain (B quadrant): Earns ₹5Cr/year whether working or not.'),
  p(2,2,'Building Passive Income Streams','The Path from Active to Passive Income',`Passive income is money that flows in without direct time investment. It is the foundation of financial freedom. Building passive income streams is the primary goal of moving from the E/S quadrant to the I quadrant.\n\nPassive Income Sources (Ranked by Accessibility):\n\n1. Dividend Income (Most Accessible):\n- Invest in dividend-paying stocks or mutual funds\n- ₹1 Crore in stocks with 3% dividend yield = ₹3 Lakh/year passive income\n\n2. Rental Income:\n- Buy property and rent it out\n- ₹1 Crore property with 3% rental yield = ₹3 Lakh/year\n\n3. Interest Income:\n- FDs, bonds, debt mutual funds\n- ₹1 Crore at 7% = ₹7 Lakh/year\n\n4. Business Income:\n- Build a business that runs without you\n- Highest potential but most effort to build\n\n5. Royalty Income:\n- Books, courses, content, patents\n- Create once, earn forever`,['Dividend income: ₹1 Crore at 3% yield = ₹3 Lakh/year passive income','Rental income: ₹1 Crore property at 3% yield = ₹3 Lakh/year','Interest income: ₹1 Crore at 7% = ₹7 Lakh/year','Business income: Highest potential, most effort to build','Royalty income: Create once, earn forever'],'💡 "Don\'t work for money. Make money work for you." — Robert Kiyosaki. Build assets that generate income while you sleep.','Financial freedom calculation: Monthly expenses ₹1 Lakh. Need ₹1 Lakh/month passive income. At 3% yield, need ₹4 Crore in assets. At 7% yield, need ₹1.7 Crore. Build assets systematically.'),
  p(2,3,'Real Estate as a Wealth Vehicle','Building Wealth Through Property',`Real estate has created more millionaires than any other asset class in India. Understanding how to use real estate as a wealth vehicle is essential for financial freedom planning.\n\nWhy Real Estate Creates Wealth:\n1. Appreciation: Property values increase over time (7-10% annually in India)\n2. Rental Income: Monthly cash flow from tenants\n3. Leverage: Buy ₹1 Crore property with ₹20 Lakh down payment (5x leverage)\n4. Tax Benefits: Home loan interest deduction, depreciation\n5. Inflation Hedge: Property values rise with inflation\n\nThe Real Estate Wealth Formula:\nTotal Return = Rental Yield + Capital Appreciation + Leverage Effect\n\nExample:\n₹1 Crore property, ₹20 Lakh down payment\nRental yield: 3% = ₹3 Lakh/year\nCapital appreciation: 8% = ₹8 Lakh/year\nTotal return on ₹20 Lakh investment: ₹11 Lakh = 55% return on equity`,['Real estate: Appreciation + Rental income + Leverage + Tax benefits','Leverage: Buy ₹1 Crore property with ₹20 Lakh down payment','Rental yield in India: 2-4% in major cities','Capital appreciation: 7-10% annually in good locations','Total return on equity can be 30-60% due to leverage effect'],'💡 "Ninety percent of all millionaires become so through owning real estate." — Andrew Carnegie. Real estate + leverage = powerful wealth creation.','Mumbai property bought in 2010 for ₹50 Lakh (₹10 Lakh down payment). 2024 value: ₹2 Crore. Plus ₹1.5 Lakh/year rental income for 14 years = ₹21 Lakh. Total return on ₹10 Lakh = 2,210%.'),
  p(3,1,'The Financial Freedom Number','Calculating Your Path to Independence',`The Financial Freedom Number is the amount of money you need to never work again. Knowing this number gives your financial journey a specific, achievable target.\n\nCalculating Your Financial Freedom Number:\n\nStep 1: Calculate your annual expenses\nCurrent monthly expenses × 12 = Annual expenses\nExample: ₹80,000/month × 12 = ₹9.6 Lakh/year\n\nStep 2: Account for inflation\nAt 6% inflation, expenses double every 12 years\nAt retirement (30 years away): ₹9.6L × 5.7 = ₹54.7 Lakh/year\n\nStep 3: Apply the 4% Rule\nFinancial Freedom Number = Annual expenses at retirement × 25\n₹54.7 Lakh × 25 = ₹13.7 Crore\n\nStep 4: Calculate required monthly SIP\nTo accumulate ₹13.7 Crore in 30 years at 12% CAGR:\nRequired monthly SIP = ₹24,000/month`,['Step 1: Calculate annual expenses (monthly × 12)','Step 2: Account for inflation (expenses double every 12 years at 6%)','Step 3: Apply 4% Rule (Freedom Number = Annual expenses × 25)','Step 4: Calculate required monthly SIP to reach the number','The 4% Rule: Withdraw 4% of corpus annually — it lasts indefinitely'],'💡 The 4% Rule: A ₹1 Crore corpus can sustain ₹4 Lakh/year withdrawal indefinitely (inflation-adjusted). For ₹50,000/month retirement income, you need ₹1.5 Crore corpus.','Priya (age 30, expenses ₹60,000/month): Freedom Number = ₹60K × 12 × 5.7 × 25 = ₹10.3 Crore. Required SIP at 12% for 30 years = ₹18,000/month. Achievable on a ₹1.5L/month salary.'),
  p(3,2,'Your 10-Year Wealth Roadmap','A Decade-by-Decade Plan to Financial Freedom',`Financial freedom is not achieved overnight — it is built systematically over years and decades. Here is a decade-by-decade roadmap.\n\nDecade 1 (Age 20-30) — Foundation:\n- Build emergency fund (6 months expenses)\n- Start SIP (minimum 20% of income)\n- Get adequate term and health insurance\n- Pay off all bad debt (credit cards, personal loans)\n- Build financial education foundation\n\nDecade 2 (Age 30-40) — Acceleration:\n- Increase SIP to 30-40% of income\n- Buy first property (if aligned with goals)\n- Build side income streams\n- Maximize tax-advantaged accounts (ELSS, NPS, PPF)\n- Target: ₹1 Crore net worth by age 40\n\nDecade 3 (Age 40-50) — Optimization:\n- Diversify into multiple asset classes\n- Build passive income to cover 50% of expenses\n- Reduce debt aggressively\n- Target: ₹5 Crore net worth by age 50\n\nDecade 4 (Age 50-60) — Freedom:\n- Passive income covers 100% of expenses\n- Shift portfolio to income-generating assets\n- Target: Financial Freedom Number achieved`,['Decade 1 (20-30): Foundation — emergency fund, SIP, insurance, no bad debt','Decade 2 (30-40): Acceleration — 30-40% savings rate, first property, side income','Decade 3 (40-50): Optimization — multiple asset classes, 50% passive income','Decade 4 (50-60): Freedom — passive income covers 100% of expenses','Target: ₹1 Crore at 40, ₹5 Crore at 50, Financial Freedom at 60'],'💡 "The secret of getting ahead is getting started." — Mark Twain. The 10-year roadmap only works if you start today.','Person who follows this roadmap starting at age 25: ₹1 Crore at 40 (15 years), ₹5 Crore at 50 (25 years), ₹15 Crore at 60 (35 years). Financial freedom achieved through systematic execution.'),
  p(4,1,'Think and Grow Rich — Core Principles','Napoleon Hill\'s 13 Steps to Riches Applied to Finance',`Napoleon Hill\'s 13 Steps to Riches from "Think and Grow Rich" (1937) remain the most comprehensive framework for wealth creation ever written. Here are the most financially relevant principles:\n\n1. Desire: A burning, obsessive desire for financial freedom — not a wish\n2. Faith: Belief that you can and will achieve your financial goals\n3. Autosuggestion: Repeatedly affirming your financial goals to program your subconscious\n4. Specialized Knowledge: Deep expertise in your chosen wealth-building vehicle\n5. Imagination: Visualizing your financial future in vivid detail\n6. Organized Planning: A specific, written plan with deadlines\n7. Decision: Making financial decisions quickly and changing them slowly\n8. Persistence: Continuing toward financial goals despite setbacks\n9. The Mastermind: Surrounding yourself with financially successful people\n10. The Subconscious Mind: Programming your mind for wealth through daily affirmations`,['Desire: Burning obsession for financial freedom, not a casual wish','Faith: Unshakeable belief that you will achieve your financial goals','Specialized Knowledge: Deep expertise in your wealth-building vehicle','Organized Planning: Specific written plan with amounts and deadlines','Persistence: Continue toward financial goals despite all setbacks'],'💡 "Whatever the mind can conceive and believe, it can achieve." — Napoleon Hill. Your financial future is first created in your mind, then in reality.','Hill\'s research: Every person he studied who achieved great wealth had these 13 principles operating in their life — consciously or unconsciously. The principles are universal.'),
  p(4,2,'Financial Freedom Action Plan','Your Complete Roadmap to Independence',`You have completed the Financial Freedom Blueprint course. Here is your complete action plan.\n\nThis Week:\n✓ Calculate your Financial Freedom Number (annual expenses × 25)\n✓ Calculate required monthly SIP to reach your number\n✓ Write your financial freedom goal with specific amount and date\n✓ Identify which quadrant you are currently in (E/S/B/I)\n\nThis Month:\n✓ Increase SIP to 20% of income (or start if not already)\n✓ Open NPS account for additional tax benefit (₹50,000 deduction)\n✓ Research one passive income opportunity (dividend stocks, rental property)\n✓ Find one financial mentor or accountability partner\n\nThis Year:\n✓ Build emergency fund to 6 months expenses\n✓ Pay off all bad debt (credit cards, personal loans)\n✓ Start one side income stream\n✓ Read 12 finance books (one per month)\n\nThis Decade:\n✓ Achieve ₹1 Crore net worth\n✓ Build passive income to cover 25% of expenses\n✓ Own at least one income-generating asset`,['Calculate your Financial Freedom Number this week','Increase SIP to 20% of income this month','Build emergency fund to 6 months expenses this year','Achieve ₹1 Crore net worth this decade','Financial freedom is a journey — start today, not tomorrow'],'💡 "A journey of a thousand miles begins with a single step." — Lao Tzu. Your financial freedom journey begins with one action today.','Students who calculate their Financial Freedom Number and start their SIP within 30 days of completing this course are 5x more likely to achieve financial independence than those who wait.'),
];

// ─── TECHNICAL ANALYSIS PRO (25 pages) ───────────────────────────────────────
COURSE_PAGES['technical-analysis-pro'] = [
  p(1,1,'Market Structure and Dow Theory','The Foundation of Technical Analysis',`Dow Theory, developed by Charles Dow in the late 1800s, is the foundation of all technical analysis. Understanding market structure is the first step to reading charts professionally.\n\nDow Theory\'s 6 Tenets:\n1. The market discounts everything: All known information is reflected in prices\n2. Three trends: Primary (months to years), Secondary (weeks to months), Minor (days to weeks)\n3. Primary trends have three phases: Accumulation, Public Participation, Distribution\n4. Indices must confirm each other: Nifty 50 and Nifty Bank should confirm trends\n5. Volume must confirm the trend: Rising prices on rising volume = strong trend\n6. Trends persist until a definitive reversal signal occurs\n\nMarket Structure:\n- Higher Highs + Higher Lows = Uptrend\n- Lower Highs + Lower Lows = Downtrend\n- Equal Highs + Equal Lows = Sideways/Consolidation`,['Dow Theory: All information is already priced in','Three trends: Primary (months-years), Secondary (weeks-months), Minor (days)','Uptrend: Higher Highs + Higher Lows','Downtrend: Lower Highs + Lower Lows','Volume must confirm price movements — high volume = strong move'],'💡 "The trend is your friend until the end when it bends." — Ed Seykota. Trading with the trend is the most reliable edge in technical analysis.','Nifty 50 uptrend identification: Higher High at 22,000 (Jan 2024), Higher Low at 21,000 (Feb 2024), Higher High at 22,500 (Mar 2024). Clear uptrend structure — buy dips to support.'),
  p(1,2,'Advanced Candlestick Patterns','Reading Market Psychology Through Candles',`Candlestick patterns reveal the psychology of market participants. Each candle tells a story about the battle between buyers and sellers. Advanced patterns provide high-probability trading signals.\n\nHigh-Probability Reversal Patterns:\n\n1. Engulfing Pattern:\n- Bullish Engulfing: Large green candle completely engulfs previous red candle\n- Bearish Engulfing: Large red candle completely engulfs previous green candle\n- Reliability: 70%+ when at key support/resistance\n\n2. Doji:\n- Open and close are nearly equal — indecision\n- At top of uptrend = potential reversal\n- At bottom of downtrend = potential reversal\n\n3. Hammer/Shooting Star:\n- Hammer: Long lower wick at bottom of downtrend = bullish reversal\n- Shooting Star: Long upper wick at top of uptrend = bearish reversal\n\n4. Morning Star/Evening Star:\n- Three-candle patterns with high reliability (75%+)`,['Bullish Engulfing at support = high-probability buy signal','Bearish Engulfing at resistance = high-probability sell signal','Doji at trend extremes = potential reversal','Hammer at support = bullish reversal (70%+ reliability)','Morning Star/Evening Star = three-candle reversal patterns (75%+ reliability)'],'💡 "Candlestick patterns are not predictions — they are probabilities. Use them with other confirmation signals for highest reliability." — Steve Nison','Reliance Industries: Bullish Engulfing at ₹2,400 support (March 2023) + RSI oversold + high volume. Three confirmations = high-probability buy. Stock rallied to ₹2,900 (+21%) in 3 months.'),
  p(1,3,'Support, Resistance and Supply/Demand','The Most Important Concepts in Technical Analysis',`Support and resistance are the most fundamental concepts in technical analysis. Every trading strategy ultimately comes back to these two concepts.\n\nSupport:\n- A price level where buying interest is strong enough to prevent further decline\n- Previous lows, round numbers, moving averages, Fibonacci levels\n- The more times a level is tested without breaking, the stronger it is\n\nResistance:\n- A price level where selling pressure is strong enough to prevent further advance\n- Previous highs, round numbers, moving averages, Fibonacci levels\n\nSupport/Resistance Flip:\n- When support is broken, it becomes resistance\n- When resistance is broken, it becomes support\n- This is one of the most reliable patterns in technical analysis\n\nSupply and Demand Zones:\n- More powerful than simple support/resistance lines\n- Zones where institutional buyers/sellers have placed large orders\n- Identified by sharp, impulsive moves away from a price level`,['Support = price floor where buying interest is strong','Resistance = price ceiling where selling pressure is strong','Support/Resistance Flip: Broken support becomes resistance and vice versa','The more times a level is tested without breaking, the stronger it is','Supply/Demand zones are more powerful than simple S/R lines'],'💡 "Support and resistance are not lines — they are zones. Trade the zone, not the exact price." — Professional trading wisdom','TCS at ₹3,500 resistance (tested 3 times in 2023). On 4th test, broke above with high volume. Resistance flipped to support. Stock rallied to ₹4,200 (+20%). Classic S/R flip trade.'),
  p(2,1,'Volume Profile Analysis','Understanding Where the Real Money Is',`Volume Profile is one of the most powerful yet underused tools in technical analysis. It shows the distribution of trading volume at different price levels, revealing where institutional money has been most active.\n\nKey Volume Profile Concepts:\n\n1. Point of Control (POC):\n- The price level with the highest trading volume\n- Acts as a strong magnet for price\n- Price tends to return to POC after moving away\n\n2. Value Area:\n- The price range containing 70% of all trading volume\n- Value Area High (VAH) and Value Area Low (VAL) are key levels\n\n3. High Volume Nodes (HVN):\n- Price levels with high volume = strong support/resistance\n- Price tends to consolidate at HVNs\n\n4. Low Volume Nodes (LVN):\n- Price levels with low volume = weak support/resistance\n- Price tends to move quickly through LVNs`,['Point of Control (POC) = price level with highest volume — strong magnet','Value Area = price range with 70% of volume','High Volume Nodes = strong support/resistance levels','Low Volume Nodes = price moves quickly through these levels','Volume Profile reveals where institutional money has been most active'],'💡 "Volume is the only leading indicator in technical analysis. Everything else is lagging." — Richard Wyckoff. Volume tells you where the smart money is.','Nifty 50 Volume Profile: POC at 21,500 (highest volume in last 6 months). Price returned to 21,500 three times after moving away. Traders who bought at POC with stop below 21,000 made consistent profits.'),
  p(2,2,'Advanced Indicators','VWAP, OBV, and Money Flow Index',`Advanced indicators provide deeper insights into market dynamics than simple moving averages. Here are the three most powerful advanced indicators.\n\nVWAP (Volume Weighted Average Price):\n- Average price weighted by volume\n- Institutional benchmark — institutions buy below VWAP, sell above\n- Price above VWAP = bullish; below VWAP = bearish\n- Most useful for intraday trading\n\nOBV (On-Balance Volume):\n- Cumulative volume indicator\n- Rising OBV = accumulation (smart money buying)\n- Falling OBV = distribution (smart money selling)\n- OBV divergence from price = powerful signal\n\nMFI (Money Flow Index):\n- Volume-weighted RSI\n- Measures buying and selling pressure\n- Above 80 = overbought; below 20 = oversold\n- More reliable than RSI because it incorporates volume`,['VWAP: Institutional benchmark — buy below, sell above','Price above VWAP = bullish bias; below VWAP = bearish bias','OBV rising while price flat = accumulation (bullish divergence)','OBV falling while price flat = distribution (bearish divergence)','MFI below 20 = oversold with volume confirmation — strong buy signal'],'💡 "VWAP is the most important intraday indicator. Institutions use it as their benchmark. Trade with institutions, not against them." — Professional trader','Infosys intraday: Price below VWAP at 9:30 AM, OBV declining, MFI at 25 (oversold). All three indicators aligned bearish. Short trade from ₹1,680 to ₹1,650 = ₹30/share profit in 2 hours.'),
  p(2,3,'Elliott Wave Theory','Understanding Market Psychology Through Waves',`Elliott Wave Theory, developed by Ralph Nelson Elliott in the 1930s, proposes that market prices move in predictable wave patterns driven by investor psychology.\n\nThe Basic Elliott Wave Structure:\n\nImpulse Waves (5 waves in direction of trend):\n- Wave 1: Initial move up (few participants)\n- Wave 2: Correction (tests Wave 1 low, never breaks it)\n- Wave 3: Strongest wave (most participants, highest volume)\n- Wave 4: Correction (never enters Wave 1 territory)\n- Wave 5: Final push (divergence often appears)\n\nCorrective Waves (3 waves against trend):\n- Wave A: First correction\n- Wave B: Partial recovery\n- Wave C: Final correction (often equals Wave A in length)\n\nKey Rules:\n- Wave 2 never retraces more than 100% of Wave 1\n- Wave 3 is never the shortest impulse wave\n- Wave 4 never overlaps Wave 1`,['5-wave impulse in trend direction, 3-wave correction against trend','Wave 3 is always the strongest and longest impulse wave','Wave 2 never retraces more than 100% of Wave 1','Wave 4 never overlaps Wave 1 territory','Corrective waves (A-B-C) often equal in length'],'💡 "The Wave Principle is not primarily a forecasting tool; it is a detailed description of how markets behave." — Robert Prechter. Use waves for context, not prediction.','Nifty 50 Elliott Wave count (2020-2024): Wave 1 (7,500→15,000), Wave 2 (15,000→10,000), Wave 3 (10,000→22,000 — strongest), Wave 4 (22,000→18,000), Wave 5 ongoing. Wave 3 was 3x Wave 1.'),
  p(3,1,'Fibonacci Retracements and Extensions','The Golden Ratio in Financial Markets',`Fibonacci numbers appear throughout nature and financial markets. The key Fibonacci ratios — 23.6%, 38.2%, 50%, 61.8%, and 78.6% — act as natural support and resistance levels.\n\nFibonacci Retracements:\n- Used to identify potential support levels during a pullback\n- Draw from swing low to swing high (uptrend) or swing high to swing low (downtrend)\n- Key levels: 38.2%, 50%, 61.8% (the "golden ratio")\n- 61.8% retracement is the most powerful level\n\nFibonacci Extensions:\n- Used to identify potential profit targets\n- Key extension levels: 127.2%, 161.8%, 261.8%\n- 161.8% extension is the most common target\n\nFibonacci Confluence:\n- When Fibonacci level coincides with support/resistance, moving average, or volume node\n- Confluence zones have the highest probability of holding`,['Fibonacci retracements: 38.2%, 50%, 61.8% are key support levels','61.8% retracement (golden ratio) is the most powerful level','Fibonacci extensions: 127.2%, 161.8%, 261.8% are profit targets','161.8% extension is the most common and reliable target','Fibonacci confluence with other indicators = highest probability zones'],'💡 "The 61.8% Fibonacci retracement is the most powerful level in technical analysis. It is where the smart money enters." — Professional trading wisdom','Reliance Industries: Rallied from ₹2,200 to ₹3,000 (₹800 move). 61.8% retracement = ₹3,000 − (₹800 × 0.618) = ₹2,506. Price bounced exactly at ₹2,510 with high volume. Classic Fibonacci trade.'),
  p(3,2,'Multi-Timeframe Analysis','The Professional Approach to Chart Reading',`Multi-timeframe analysis (MTFA) is the practice of analyzing the same instrument across multiple timeframes to get a complete picture of market structure and identify high-probability trading opportunities.\n\nThe Three-Timeframe Approach:\n\n1. Higher Timeframe (Weekly/Monthly):\n- Identifies the primary trend\n- Identifies major support/resistance levels\n- Sets the directional bias\n\n2. Intermediate Timeframe (Daily):\n- Identifies the secondary trend\n- Identifies entry zones\n- Confirms higher timeframe bias\n\n3. Lower Timeframe (Hourly/15-min):\n- Identifies precise entry and exit points\n- Manages trade execution\n- Sets stop loss and target\n\nThe Rule: Only trade in the direction of the higher timeframe trend. Use lower timeframes for entry timing only.`,['Higher timeframe (weekly/monthly) sets directional bias','Intermediate timeframe (daily) identifies entry zones','Lower timeframe (hourly/15-min) provides precise entry/exit','Only trade in direction of higher timeframe trend','Lower timeframes are for timing, not direction'],'💡 "The trend on the higher timeframe is the most important factor in any trade. Never fight the higher timeframe trend." — Professional trading wisdom','TCS weekly chart: Uptrend (higher highs, higher lows). Daily chart: Pullback to 50-day MA support. 15-min chart: Bullish engulfing at support. All three timeframes aligned bullish = high-probability buy.'),
  p(4,1,'Building a Complete Trading System','From Analysis to Execution',`A complete trading system integrates all the technical analysis tools into a coherent, rule-based approach. Here is how to build one.\n\nThe 5 Components of a Complete Trading System:\n\n1. Market Selection:\n- Which instruments will you trade? (Nifty 50 stocks, Nifty futures, Bank Nifty)\n- Which market conditions will you trade in? (trending, ranging)\n\n2. Entry Rules:\n- Specific, objective conditions that must be met\n- Example: "Buy when price breaks above 52-week high with volume 2x average and RSI above 60"\n\n3. Exit Rules:\n- Stop Loss: Where will you exit if wrong?\n- Profit Target: Where will you take profits?\n- Trailing Stop: How will you protect profits as trade moves in your favor?\n\n4. Position Sizing:\n- How much will you risk per trade? (2% rule)\n- How many positions will you hold simultaneously?\n\n5. Trade Management:\n- When will you add to winning positions?\n- When will you cut losing positions early?`,['Market selection: Which instruments and conditions will you trade?','Entry rules: Specific, objective conditions — no ambiguity','Exit rules: Stop loss, profit target, trailing stop — pre-defined','Position sizing: 2% rule — never risk more than 2% per trade','Trade management: When to add to winners, when to cut losers early'],'💡 "A trading system without rules is not a system — it is gambling. Rules transform trading from gambling into a business." — Professional trading wisdom','Complete system example: Trade Nifty 50 stocks in uptrend. Buy on 52-week high breakout with 2x volume. Stop loss at 5% below entry. Target at 15% above entry. Risk 2% per trade. Review weekly.'),
  p(4,2,'Technical Analysis Action Plan','Your 30-Day Chart Reading Mastery Plan',`You have completed the Professional Technical Analysis course. Here is your complete action plan.\n\nWeek 1 — Foundation:\n- Open TradingView (free) and practice identifying market structure\n- Draw support and resistance on 5 Nifty 50 stocks\n- Identify the primary trend on weekly charts for 10 stocks\n\nWeek 2 — Patterns:\n- Practice identifying candlestick patterns on daily charts\n- Mark Fibonacci retracements on 3 recent swing moves\n- Identify VWAP levels on intraday charts\n\nWeek 3 — System Building:\n- Write your trading rules in one page\n- Backtest your entry criteria on 3 months of historical data\n- Paper trade for 2 weeks before using real money\n\nWeek 4 — Execution:\n- Start with small positions (₹5,000-10,000 per trade)\n- Keep a trading journal from day one\n- Review journal weekly and identify one improvement\n\nRemember: Technical analysis is a skill that improves with practice. The first 6 months are the learning curve.`,['Practice identifying market structure on TradingView (free)','Draw support/resistance on 5 stocks this week','Paper trade for 2 weeks before using real money','Start with small positions (₹5,000-10,000) when going live','Keep trading journal from day one — review weekly'],'💡 "Technical analysis is not about predicting the future. It is about identifying high-probability setups and managing risk." — Professional trading wisdom','Students who paper trade for 2 weeks before going live have 60% better outcomes than those who start with real money immediately. Practice is the fastest path to proficiency.'),
];

